-- ============================================================
-- Batch 21: 25 curated AI tools (Step 41 — scale to 1,500)
-- Hand-authored enrichment via parallel research. Every tool has a
-- live affiliate program (FirstPromoter / PartnerStack / Impact /
-- in-house) AND fills a category gap from batches 1–20: voice/video
-- avatars, email/CRM, course platforms, communities, funnels,
-- scheduling, forms, product analytics. All slugs deduped vs the
-- existing 1,065-tool catalog (post-042).
-- All website_url values are bare canonical domains — no UTM, no ref,
-- no affiliate redirector. Affiliate program metadata tracked separately
-- in RightAIChoice_Affiliate_Master.xlsx.
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO tools (
  name, slug, tagline, description, website_url,
  pricing_type, pricing_details, skill_level, has_api, platforms,
  features, integrations, is_published,
  best_for, not_for, editorial_verdict,
  tutorial_urls, limitations, models, community_links, use_cases, our_views,
  last_verified_at
) VALUES
('Tavus', 'tavus', 'API-first conversational video platform that turns scripts into personalised AI video and real-time digital twins.', 'Tavus is a developer-focused AI video platform that pioneered two distinct surfaces: programmatic personalised video (record one base video, generate thousands of variants with name / company / context swapped per recipient) and a Conversational Video Interface (CVI) that lets a digital twin of a real person hold a real-time, two-way video conversation over WebRTC. Both are exposed primarily through a REST API and SDKs rather than a no-code dashboard, which is what separates Tavus from Synthesia / HeyGen in the market.

The CVI stack — Phoenix (rendering), Sparrow (turn-taking), Raven (perception) — handles speech recognition, natural turn-taking, sub-second latency, and lip-sync at production quality, which makes it credible for live use cases like AI sales reps, recruiter screening calls, customer-onboarding agents, and interactive learning tutors. Personal Replicas are trained from a short consent video of the source person and can be re-used across thousands of generations, with built-in consent and watermarking for safety.

Tavus'' position in 2026 is the API-first leader for real-time conversational video. Synthesia owns the marketing-video lane and HeyGen owns the creator lane; Tavus owns the engineering lane — startups building agentic video products almost always evaluate Tavus first because the API surface and replica quality are ahead of competitors. The B2B affiliate program is a fit for sales-tech, dev-tool, and AI-newsletter audiences.', 'https://www.tavus.io', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["25 CVI minutes","5 stock replicas","3 minutes of video generation","Developer sandbox"]},{"plan":"Starter","price":"$59/mo","features":["100 CVI minutes","3 concurrent streams","3 personal replicas","Pay-as-you-go overage"]},{"plan":"Growth","price":"$397/mo","features":["1,250 CVI minutes","15 concurrent streams","10 personal replicas","Discounted overage"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["SOC2 / HIPAA","White-label","Dedicated support","Custom replica volume"]}]'::jsonb, 'advanced', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Conversational Video Interface (real-time two-way video with a digital twin)","Phoenix rendering engine for sub-second latency","Personal Replicas trained from short consent video","Programmatic personalised video generation at scale","REST API and SDKs (Python, Node, React)","WebRTC streaming for live conversations","Multi-language replica support (30+ languages)","Built-in consent capture and watermarking","Webhook events for video lifecycle","Stock replica library for fast prototyping"}', '{"Twilio","LiveKit","Daily.co","Zapier","HubSpot","Salesforce","Slack","Webhooks","REST API"}', true, '{"AI engineering teams building real-time video agents","Sales-tech vendors adding personalised video outreach","Recruiting platforms automating first-round screens","EdTech products needing interactive AI tutors"}', '{"Marketers who want a no-code video editor (use Synthesia)","Solo creators making YouTube content (use HeyGen)","Teams without engineering capacity to integrate an API"}', 'The strongest API-first conversational video platform in 2026 — pick it if you''re building a product, skip it if you just want to record talking-head videos.', '{"https://docs.tavus.io/"}', 'CVI minutes burn fast in real production — a single 5-minute customer-support session per user across a 1,000-user week is 5,000 minutes, which sits firmly in Growth-plus territory and adds up. Personal Replica training requires careful consent video capture; off-spec recordings produce visible artefacts in the lower face. Real-time CVI quality degrades on weak networks (sub-2 Mbps) and the platform doesn''t auto-fall-back to text. Documentation is engineer-grade — non-developers will need help integrating.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Embed an AI sales rep that holds live discovery calls inside a SaaS pricing page.","Generate 5,000 personalised onboarding videos from one base script using merge fields.","Run an AI recruiter that screens candidates over a 10-minute video conversation.","Build an interactive AI tutor that responds to learner questions in real time."}', 'Sweet spot: a venture-funded AI startup or product team building a feature where a digital human needs to hold a real-time conversation — sales agent, recruiter, tutor, support concierge. Tavus'' CVI is the only credible turn-key stack for that use case in 2026 without stitching together five vendors (TTS + STT + LLM + avatar + WebRTC). The API quality and replica fidelity justify the pricing for teams shipping real product.

Failure modes to know. First, latency budgets are tight — anything beyond Tavus'' control (your LLM call, your retrieval layer, your network) eats into the 1.5-second turn-taking window and the conversation feels laggy. Second, the unit economics only work if your average session is short or your ARPU is high; long free-tier consumer sessions will bleed margin. Third, the consent and watermarking workflow is correct but adds UX friction — bake it into onboarding rather than bolting it on later.

What to pilot before committing. Build a 30-day prototype using one Personal Replica for a single high-value use case (a single sales motion, a single onboarding flow). Measure CVI minutes consumed, completion rate, and the qualitative reaction from real users. If users finish the conversation and convert at meaningfully higher rates than the text baseline, scale up. If they drop off mid-call, the failure is product fit, not Tavus.', now()),
('Vidyard', 'vidyard', 'AI video messaging and prospecting platform built for B2B sales teams.', 'Vidyard is the long-running leader in async video for sales — the Chrome-extension webcam recorder that lets a sales rep record a personalised video, drop it into an email or LinkedIn message, and track exactly when the prospect watches it. The 2026 product has expanded well beyond the original recorder: Vidyard now includes AI Avatars (generate spokesperson video from a script without filming), AI Script Generator (drafts a tailored video script from a prospect''s LinkedIn profile or company URL), and a Video Sales Agent that triggers personalised videos automatically when a prospect performs a buying signal like visiting the pricing page.

The platform integrates deeply with the sales stack — Salesforce, HubSpot, Outreach, Salesloft, Gong, LinkedIn Sales Navigator — so video opens, watch percentage, and CTA clicks flow back into the rep''s CRM and trigger sequences. Hosting is enterprise-grade with custom branding, password protection, lead-capture forms, calls-to-action, and detailed engagement analytics down to the second of viewing.

Vidyard''s position in 2026 is the dominant async-video tool in B2B sales workflows. Loom owns the internal-collaboration use case; Vidyard owns the sales-outreach use case. The PartnerStack-managed affiliate program pays recurring commission and is a strong fit for sales-tech and SDR-training audiences.', 'https://www.vidyard.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Unlimited recordings","Basic analytics","Chrome extension","25 stock AI avatar videos"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$19/user/mo","features":["Custom branding","CTAs","Email and calendar integrations","Stock AI avatars"]},{"plan":"Plus","price":"$59/user/mo","features":["Salesforce / HubSpot sync","Advanced analytics","Custom AI avatars (15 videos)","Lead capture"]},{"plan":"Teams","price":"$99/user/mo","features":["Outreach / Salesloft sync","Team analytics","Video Sales Agent (add-on)","SSO"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api","plugin"}', '{"Chrome extension for instant webcam + screen recording","AI Script Generator (writes from LinkedIn / URL)","AI Avatars (stock and custom)","Video Sales Agent — automated personalised video on buyer signals","Per-second engagement analytics","CRM sync (Salesforce, HubSpot, Outreach, Salesloft)","Custom branded video player","Password protection and viewer gating","Lead-capture forms and CTAs inside the player","Mobile recorder app"}', '{"Salesforce","HubSpot","Outreach","Salesloft","Gmail","Outlook","LinkedIn Sales Navigator","Gong","Slack","Zapier"}', true, '{"B2B SDRs personalising cold outreach at scale","Account executives sending follow-up videos after demos","Customer success managers running async QBRs","RevOps teams measuring video influence on pipeline"}', '{"Internal team collaboration (Loom is cheaper and lighter)","Marketing video hosting on a brand site (Wistia fits better)","Solo creators publishing to YouTube"}', 'The default async-video tool for B2B sales in 2026 — pick it if your reps actually use video in outreach, skip it if you just need a Loom replacement for internal updates.', '{"https://knowledge.vidyard.com/"}', 'Per-seat pricing scales aggressively — a 50-rep team on Plus is $35K+/year before the Video Sales Agent add-on, which adds custom-priced volume on top. Custom AI avatars are limited to 15 videos on lower tiers; unlimited generation requires the agent add-on or Enterprise. Free-tier analytics are thin and the Chrome extension occasionally breaks on Gmail UI updates. Several mid-market customers report that ROI only shows up when reps use video weekly — sporadic usage doesn''t justify the seat cost.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Send a personalised 60-second cold-outreach video to 100 named accounts.","Trigger a follow-up video automatically when a prospect re-visits the pricing page.","Record an async demo recap that the buying committee can share internally.","Generate a stock-avatar product-explainer video without filming a rep."}', 'Sweet spot: a B2B sales org with 10–200 reps where async video is part of the outbound or post-demo motion. Vidyard pays for itself when reply rates lift 1.5–3x on cold outreach (typical lift on warm-ish accounts) or when post-demo videos materially shorten sales cycles by getting the buying committee aligned faster. The CRM sync is the actual moat — the analytics being inside Salesforce is what gets RevOps to defend the line item.

Failure modes. First, the seat cost only works if reps record weekly — pilots that fizzle to one video a month produce CFO eyebrow-raising. Mandate a usage floor before rollout. Second, the AI Script Generator and stock avatars produce competent but obviously-AI output; using them on top-tier accounts is reputationally risky. Save AI generation for top-of-funnel volume, not strategic deals. Third, the Video Sales Agent add-on is custom-priced and can balloon costs once usage scales — model it before signing.

What to pilot. Pick one SDR pod (5–8 reps), one outbound sequence, and one set of accounts. Run a 60-day A/B: half the pod uses Vidyard at every personalised step, half uses text only. Measure reply rate, meeting-booked rate, and pipeline created. If video lifts at least one metric by 50%+, expand to the rest of the team. If lift is sub-20%, the bottleneck is messaging or targeting, not the medium.', now()),
('Wistia', 'wistia', 'B2B-focused video hosting platform with built-in AI chapters, transcripts, summaries, and lead capture.', 'Wistia is a long-running B2B video hosting platform that has quietly become the default video CMS for marketing teams who need their videos to do more than play. The 2026 product is a full video marketing suite: hosting with custom-branded player, lead-capture forms inside the player (Turnstile), CTAs, end-screen actions, password protection, A/B testing, and detailed engagement analytics that flow into HubSpot / Marketo / Pardot for lead scoring.

The AI layer added across 2024–2026 is now central to the product: AI auto-generates chapters, full transcripts (90+ languages), captions, video summaries for description fields, and short-form clips suitable for social. The Channels feature lets teams build a branded Netflix-style video hub on their own domain, which is a popular alternative to YouTube for product-led B2B marketing where you don''t want competitor videos in the recommendations sidebar.

Wistia''s position in 2026 is the marketing-team video CMS. YouTube wins reach; Vimeo wins creator-pro use cases; Wistia wins when the video has to capture leads, sync watch-time to the CRM, and live on a brand-controlled domain. The Impact-managed affiliate program is a good fit for B2B marketing publishers and SaaS-stack reviewers.', 'https://wistia.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["10 videos","25 GB storage","AI transcripts and chapters","Basic analytics"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$79/mo","features":["50 videos","Custom branding","Lead capture (Turnstile)","HubSpot / Marketo integrations"]},{"plan":"Advanced","price":"$319/mo","features":["250 videos","Channels","A/B testing","Advanced analytics"]},{"plan":"Premium","price":"Custom","features":["Unlimited videos","SSO","SLA","Dedicated CSM"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Custom-branded HTML5 video player","AI auto-generated chapters","AI transcripts and captions (90+ languages)","AI video summaries for descriptions and metadata","AI short-clip generator for social","Turnstile lead-capture forms inside player","Calls-to-action and end-screen actions","Channels — Netflix-style branded video hubs","A/B testing on player and thumbnails","Per-second engagement heatmaps"}', '{"HubSpot","Marketo","Pardot","Salesforce","Mailchimp","WordPress","Zapier","Google Analytics","Slack","Webhooks"}', true, '{"B2B marketing teams running gated demand-gen video","Product marketers hosting product tours and feature reels","Customer education teams running on-domain video hubs","SaaS companies replacing YouTube on their own site"}', '{"Solo creators chasing YouTube reach and discoverability","Consumer media companies needing massive CDN volume","Teams that don''t need lead capture or CRM sync (use Vimeo / Bunny)"}', 'The strongest video CMS for B2B marketing in 2026 — pick it when video has to capture leads and sync to a CRM, skip it when you just need cheap hosting.', '{"https://wistia.com/support"}', 'Pricing jumps steeply between tiers — the Pro plan''s 50-video cap is hit fast by any active marketing team, and the Advanced plan at $319/month is a real line item. AI summaries occasionally hallucinate specifics from poorly-transcribed audio; always human-review before publishing. Channels are a strong feature but customisation is constrained — heavily branded sites may chafe at the templating. CDN performance is excellent in North America and Europe but noticeably weaker in Asia-Pacific without Premium-tier multi-region delivery.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Host a gated product demo that captures email and pushes the lead to HubSpot.","Build a branded Channels hub for customer education videos on your own domain.","Auto-chapter and transcribe a 60-minute webinar for SEO and accessibility.","A/B test two thumbnails on a homepage hero video and ship the winner."}', 'Sweet spot: a B2B SaaS marketing team with 20–500 videos in active rotation that needs the videos to do real demand-gen work — capture leads, push to CRM, drive lifecycle stages. Wistia''s value is in everything that happens around the player, not the player itself. Teams that just want a hosting URL are overpaying; teams that want the video to be a demand surface are underpaying.

Failure modes. First, the AI chapter and summary features are good but not infallible — for thought-leadership content from execs, treat AI output as a first draft and have a human edit before publishing externally. Second, Channels gets pitched as a YouTube replacement, but discovery still mostly happens on YouTube; Channels works as a brand-owned destination, not a top-of-funnel acquisition channel. Third, scaling past 250 videos pushes you to Premium quickly, and Premium is custom-priced — model the trajectory before signing a multi-year deal.

What to pilot. Take your highest-traffic gated video asset (likely a product demo or webinar replay). Move it from YouTube / Vimeo to Wistia, wire Turnstile to HubSpot, and measure form-fill rate and downstream MQL→SQL conversion versus the previous host over 60 days. If form-fill rate lifts 30%+ and the leads convert at the same rate, the per-month cost is justified across the rest of your library. If lift is marginal, the value isn''t in the player switch — it''s upstream in the offer.', now()),
('Kit (formerly ConvertKit)', 'kit', 'Creator-first email marketing and audience platform — the rebranded ConvertKit, built for newsletters, courses, and digital products.', 'Kit (rebranded from ConvertKit in late 2024) is the email marketing platform of choice for the creator economy — newsletter writers, course creators, podcasters, authors, and indie SaaS founders who sell directly to an audience. The product is built around three primitives: subscribers (tagged and segmented, never duplicated across lists), sequences (visual automation flows for onboarding, courses, launches), and broadcasts (one-off newsletter sends). The data model is intentionally simpler than HubSpot or ActiveCampaign — no contact-vs-lead distinction, no separate "lists" — which is what makes it fast for solo creators to operate.

Beyond email, Kit ships landing pages, sign-up forms, a Link-in-Bio-style Creator Profile, paid newsletter subscriptions (Stripe-integrated), digital product sales (no Gumroad needed), tip jars, and the Creator Network — a recommendations engine that has driven millions of cross-creator subscriber referrals. The 2024–2026 rebrand to "Kit" reflected the platform''s expansion from pure email tool to creator operating system.

Kit''s position in 2026 is the dominant ESP for creators above the Substack tier — anyone who outgrows Substack''s no-automation simplicity but doesn''t want enterprise CRM bloat lands here. Beehiiv competes hard on price and growth tools; Kit holds the lead on automation depth and creator-network referrals. The PartnerStack-managed affiliate program pays recurring commission and is one of the highest-converting in the creator-tools category.', 'https://kit.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Newsletter (Free)","price":"$0","features":["Up to 10,000 subscribers","Unlimited broadcasts","Landing pages and forms","1 automation"]},{"plan":"Creator","price":"$39/mo (1K subs)","features":["Unlimited automations","Visual automation builder","Free migration","Creator Network referrals"]},{"plan":"Creator Pro","price":"$59/mo (1K subs)","features":["Subscriber scoring","Advanced reporting","Newsletter referral system","Facebook custom audiences"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Visual automation sequence builder","Subscriber tagging and segmentation","Landing pages and sign-up forms","Creator Profile (Link-in-Bio replacement)","Paid newsletter subscriptions (Stripe)","Digital product and tip-jar sales","Creator Network — cross-creator recommendations","Subscriber scoring (Pro)","Deliverability dashboard","REST API and webhooks"}', '{"Stripe","Shopify","WordPress","Teachable","Thinkific","Zapier","Webhooks","Calendly","Patreon","Squarespace"}', true, '{"Newsletter writers monetising a 1K–500K-subscriber audience","Course creators running launch sequences and evergreen funnels","Authors and podcasters building direct reader relationships","Indie SaaS founders running lifecycle email"}', '{"E-commerce stores needing transactional templates (use Klaviyo)","Enterprise B2B teams needing CRM-grade sales automation","Hyper-cost-conscious creators under 1K subs (use MailerLite or Beehiiv free)"}', 'The default email platform for serious creators in 2026 — pick it when your business is your audience, skip it when your business is e-commerce SKUs or B2B sales.', '{"https://help.kit.com/"}', 'Pricing scales by subscriber count regardless of whether those subscribers open emails — pruning is essential and Kit''s tooling for re-engagement / sunset is workable but not best-in-class. Visual automation builder is solid but lacks the conditional-split depth of ActiveCampaign for complex B2B journeys. Creator Network recommendations drive real subscriber growth but the matching algorithm is a black box and quality varies by niche. Email template editor is functional but design-constrained vs Beehiiv''s newer block editor.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run a 7-email course-launch sequence triggered by a free lead-magnet opt-in.","Send a weekly broadcast newsletter to 25,000 subscribers with embedded paid-product CTAs.","Sell a $29 ebook directly from Kit with Stripe checkout and an automated delivery email.","Grow the list 20%/year via Creator Network recommendations from peer newsletters."}', 'Sweet spot: a creator with 1K–100K engaged subscribers whose business is some mix of newsletter, course, ebook, or community — meaning email is the primary revenue channel, not a marketing afterthought. Kit''s automation depth and creator-native primitives (digital products, paid subs, Creator Profile, Network) collapse what would otherwise be Substack + Gumroad + Linktree + Mailchimp into one bill, which is what justifies the per-subscriber pricing.

Failure modes. First, the per-subscriber pricing punishes list bloat — if 40% of your list never opens, you''re paying full price to host dead weight. Set a quarterly sunset rule and automate it. Second, the Creator Network is a real growth lever in some niches (business, productivity, finance, writing) and a graveyard in others (hyper-narrow B2B, regional consumer); audit cohort quality after 60 days. Third, the rebrand from ConvertKit to Kit confused some long-time customers and SEO equity took a hit — search-driven discovery of help docs is worse than it was in 2023.

What to pilot. Migrate your existing list (Kit offers free done-for-you migration above 5K subscribers). Re-build your top-performing automation sequence and your weekly broadcast. After 60 days, compare deliverability (inbox placement), open rate, click rate, and revenue-per-subscriber against the previous platform. If two of those four numbers improve and the Creator Network adds 5%+ subscribers, Kit is the right home. If numbers are flat, the platform isn''t the bottleneck — your offer or copy is.', now()),
('MailerLite', 'mailerlite', 'Affordable email marketing platform with AI subject-line writer, drag-and-drop builder, and a generous free tier.', 'MailerLite is a Lithuania-based email marketing platform that has held a clear positioning for over a decade: clean UX, transparent pricing, generous free tier, and feature parity with most expensive competitors at roughly half the price. The 2026 product covers the full small-business email stack — drag-and-drop email builder, automation workflows, landing pages, embeddable websites, signup forms and pop-ups, A/B testing, segmentation, and an AI assistant that writes subject lines, email body copy, and full campaign drafts inside the editor.

The free tier is unusually generous (500 subscribers, 12,000 emails/month, drag-and-drop editor, automation, landing pages) and is a primary acquisition channel. Paid plans start at $10/month for 500 subscribers and scale linearly with list size; the Advanced tier ($20/month entry) unlocks the AI writing assistant, custom HTML editor, multi-trigger automations, and unlimited user seats. E-commerce features include Shopify / WooCommerce sync, abandoned cart automations, and product blocks inside emails.

MailerLite''s position in 2026 is the value tier for small businesses and bootstrapped operators. Mailchimp has drifted upmarket and got expensive; Brevo competes on price but has a clunkier UX; Kit owns creators. MailerLite owns the long tail of small e-commerce stores, local services, freelancers, and side projects. The in-house affiliate program pays 30% recurring lifetime commission, which is one of the most generous in the email-marketing category.', 'https://www.mailerlite.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["500 subscribers","12,000 emails/mo","Drag-and-drop editor","Automation builder","Landing pages"]},{"plan":"Growing Business","price":"$10/mo (500 subs)","features":["Unlimited monthly emails","3 user seats","Unlimited templates","Auto-resend","Multivariate testing"]},{"plan":"Advanced","price":"$20/mo (500 subs)","features":["AI writing assistant","Custom HTML","Unlimited users","Multi-trigger automation","Live chat support"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["100K+ subscribers","Dedicated IP","Account manager","Design services"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Drag-and-drop email builder with block library","AI subject-line generator","AI campaign and copy writer (Advanced tier)","Visual automation builder","Landing pages and embeddable websites","Sign-up forms and pop-ups","A/B and multivariate testing","E-commerce blocks and abandoned-cart flows","Subscriber segmentation and tagging","Transactional email API (MailerSend integration)"}', '{"Shopify","WooCommerce","WordPress","Stripe","Zapier","Make","Squarespace","Webflow","Calendly","Wix"}', true, '{"Small e-commerce stores running newsletters and abandoned-cart flows","Bootstrapped SaaS founders managing lifecycle email under $50/mo","Freelancers and consultants nurturing a small client list","Side-project newsletters that outgrew Substack''s send limits"}', '{"Enterprise teams needing CRM-grade segmentation (use HubSpot)","Creators selling courses and digital products (Kit fits better)","High-volume transactional senders (use MailerSend / Postmark directly)"}', 'The most generous free tier and best price-per-feature in email marketing in 2026 — pick it when budget is the constraint, skip it when you need creator-native commerce or enterprise CRM.', '{"https://www.mailerlite.com/help"}', 'Approval process for new accounts is strict — affiliate marketers, MLM senders, and unverified niches get rejected, sometimes after building campaigns. The AI writing assistant is competent but produces generic copy compared to GPT-4-class direct prompting; treat it as a starter, not a finisher. Segmentation is solid for small lists but lacks the multi-condition depth needed for complex B2B journeys. Deliverability is generally strong but shared-IP placement on the lowest tiers can suffer in some Gmail tabs without warmup hygiene.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Send a weekly Shopify-store newsletter to 5,000 subscribers with product blocks.","Build an abandoned-cart automation that recovers 8–12% of lost checkouts.","Run a 5-email welcome sequence triggered by a landing-page form sign-up.","A/B test three subject-line variants generated by the AI assistant on a launch broadcast."}', 'Sweet spot: a small business or solo operator under 25K subscribers running e-commerce or newsletter email on a tight budget. MailerLite''s value is the unit economics — at $10–$50/month you get the same core capabilities (automation, landing pages, A/B testing, segmentation) that Mailchimp and ActiveCampaign charge 3–5x for. The free tier is good enough to run a real business on, which is rare in this category.

Failure modes. First, the strict approval process trips up legitimate edge cases — affiliate-heavy niches, anything adjacent to crypto / supplements / "make money online" gets flagged and accounts can be paused mid-campaign. Vet your niche fit before committing. Second, the AI writing assistant hides on the Advanced tier and isn''t worth the upgrade by itself — most users get better output from a $20/month ChatGPT Plus subscription pasted into the free editor. Third, support response times stretch on lower tiers; live chat is Advanced-only.

What to pilot. Run your existing newsletter and one automation flow on the free tier for 30 days. Compare deliverability (inbox placement using Glock Apps or similar), open rate, and click rate against your current platform. If numbers are at parity, the per-month savings vs Mailchimp / ActiveCampaign justify the switch immediately. If deliverability dips noticeably, stay on shared IP with a heavier warmup or upgrade to a tier with better placement.', now()),
('GetResponse', 'getresponse', 'Email marketing platform with automation, funnels, webinars, and AI-generated emails and landing pages.', 'GetResponse is a long-running European email-marketing platform (Polish-founded, 1998) that has steadily expanded from pure newsletter sending into a full marketing suite: email campaigns, marketing automation workflows, conversion funnels, landing pages, signup forms, paid-ads integration, live and on-demand webinars, and a built-in CRM. The 2024–2026 product line layers AI throughout — an AI Email Generator that drafts subject lines and body copy from a brief, an AI Landing Page Creator that produces a full page from a goal description, and AI subject-line scoring that predicts open-rate uplift before send.

The platform is positioned for SMBs, course creators, ecommerce operators, and B2B teams that want one tool for the whole acquisition-to-nurture stack rather than stitching together Mailchimp + ClickFunnels + Zoom Webinars + a separate CRM. The webinar module is the most differentiated piece — few email tools include a real, native webinar product — and the Conversion Funnels feature templatises the lead-magnet → email-sequence → sales flow that most marketers build manually.

GetResponse runs an in-house affiliate program with a 33% recurring commission tier, which has made it a perennial favourite in the affiliate-marketing community. The product''s longevity (28+ years in business) and European data residency are real advantages for GDPR-sensitive teams.', 'https://www.getresponse.com', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Email Marketing","price":"$19/mo","features":["Up to 1,000 contacts","Unlimited newsletters","AI Email Generator","Signup forms and popups","Website builder"]},{"plan":"Marketing Automation","price":"$59/mo","features":["Automation workflows","Webinars (up to 100 attendees)","Sales funnels","Event-based segmentation","Contact scoring"]},{"plan":"Ecommerce Marketing","price":"$119/mo","features":["Quick transactional emails","Abandoned cart recovery","Promo codes","Web push notifications","Product recommendations"]},{"plan":"GetResponse MAX","price":"Custom","features":["Dedicated IP","SSO","Transactional email API","Priority support","Custom onboarding"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"AI Email Generator (subject lines and body)","AI Landing Page Creator","Drag-and-drop email and automation builder","Native webinar hosting (live and on-demand)","Conversion Funnels with prebuilt templates","Marketing automation workflows","Landing pages and forms builder","Built-in CRM and contact scoring","Ecommerce features (cart abandonment, product recs)","Web push notifications","SMS marketing","Paid ads integration (Facebook, Google)"}', '{"Shopify","WooCommerce","WordPress","Stripe","PayPal","Zapier","Salesforce","Magento","BigCommerce","Google Analytics"}', true, '{"SMBs wanting one tool for email plus webinars plus funnels","Course creators bundling email nurture with live webinars","Affiliate marketers running lead-magnet funnels","European teams that need GDPR-friendly data residency"}', '{"Enterprise teams needing best-in-class deliverability (Klaviyo / Iterable win)","Pure transactional email use cases (Postmark / SendGrid fit better)","Ecommerce stores already deep on Klaviyo flows"}', 'A solid all-in-one for SMBs that want email, automation, and webinars under one roof — not the deliverability leader, but the breadth-per-dollar is hard to match.', '{"https://www.getresponse.com/help"}', 'Deliverability is good but not Klaviyo / Iterable tier — high-stakes ecommerce senders sometimes report better inbox rates elsewhere. The all-in-one breadth means individual modules (CRM, webinars) are competent rather than best-in-class — power users of any single function may outgrow the bundle. AI features are useful for first drafts but produce generic output without careful prompting. Pricing scales aggressively with contact count once you cross 25K subscribers, and the Ecommerce tier is required for the most useful revenue features.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run a 5-email welcome sequence with native webinar registration as the conversion goal.","Build a complete lead-magnet funnel — landing page, opt-in form, nurture sequence, sales page — without leaving the tool.","Host a live product webinar to 500 attendees and follow up with a segmented replay sequence.","Recover abandoned shopping carts on a Shopify store with automated discount-code emails."}', 'Sweet spot: a 1–10 person SMB or solo course creator who currently pays for three or four overlapping tools (Mailchimp + ClickFunnels + Zoom + a CRM) and wants to consolidate. GetResponse won''t beat any individual specialist tool, but the consolidated bill and the single-system reporting are real wins, and the native webinar capability is genuinely rare in this category.

Failure modes. The biggest one is buying GetResponse expecting Klaviyo-class ecommerce automation — the flows exist but the depth of segmentation, predictive analytics, and Shopify-native integrations are weaker. The webinar module works but isn''t a Zoom replacement for high-stakes events (capacity, network resilience, integrations). And the AI generators are productivity helpers, not voice-trained writers — outputs need real editing.

What to pilot. Take the 30-day trial and rebuild your single most-used current funnel inside GetResponse end-to-end (landing page, opt-in, 5-email sequence, webinar invite). Compare conversion rates and the time-to-build against your current stack. If the consolidated workflow saves you meaningful hours per week and the conversion rates hold, the switch pays for itself by removing 2–3 other subscriptions.', now()),
('Reply.io', 'reply-io', 'AI sales engagement platform for multichannel outbound across email, LinkedIn, calls, and SMS.', 'Reply.io is a sales engagement platform built for outbound SDR teams running multichannel sequences — email, LinkedIn touches, calls, SMS, and WhatsApp — across hundreds or thousands of prospects. The 2024–2026 product is built around an AI SDR called Jason that can research a prospect, write a personalised opener, send through whichever channel scores highest for that contact, and book qualified meetings on a calendar without a human in the loop. Human SDRs use the same engine as a copilot inside the sequence editor.

The platform handles the unsexy plumbing of cold outreach well: inbox warm-up, deliverability monitoring, mailbox rotation across multiple sending domains, A/B testing of subject lines and openers, calendar booking, CRM sync (HubSpot, Salesforce, Pipedrive), and a built-in B2B contact database for prospect discovery. Sequences mix automated steps with manual tasks (e.g., "send a personalised LinkedIn voice note") so reps can stay efficient without sounding robotic.

Reply.io is one of the most-recommended tools in the SDR community on Reddit, LinkedIn, and dedicated sales communities. The PartnerStack-managed affiliate program is widely promoted by sales-tooling reviewers. Pricing is per-user and scales steeply at higher tiers, which is the main reason teams either commit fully or churn after a quarter.', 'https://reply.io', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Email Volume","price":"$59/mo","features":["1,000 active contacts","Unlimited mailboxes","Email warm-up","Basic AI features"]},{"plan":"Multichannel","price":"$99/user/mo","features":["Email plus LinkedIn plus calls plus SMS","AI sequence generator","CRM integrations","Meeting booker"]},{"plan":"Agency","price":"$166/user/mo","features":["Multi-client workspaces","White-label reporting","Priority support","Advanced API"]},{"plan":"AI SDR (Jason)","price":"From $300/mo","features":["Autonomous prospect research","Multichannel auto-outreach","Meeting booking","Custom training on ICP"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Multichannel sequences (email, LinkedIn, calls, SMS, WhatsApp)","AI SDR (Jason) for autonomous outreach","AI-generated sequence and email copy","Inbox warm-up and deliverability monitoring","Mailbox rotation across multiple domains","Built-in B2B contact database","Calendar and meeting booker","A/B testing on subject lines and openers","CRM sync (HubSpot, Salesforce, Pipedrive)","Call dialer with recording and transcription","Reply detection and sentiment analysis","Team analytics dashboards"}', '{"HubSpot","Salesforce","Pipedrive","Gmail","Outlook","LinkedIn Sales Navigator","Slack","Zapier","Vidyard","Calendly"}', true, '{"Outbound SDR teams running multichannel sequences","B2B founders doing founder-led sales at 100+ contacts/week","Sales agencies running outbound for multiple clients","RevOps teams that need warm-up plus deliverability tooling built in"}', '{"Inbound-only sales motions (overkill — use HubSpot Sales Hub)","Solo founders with under 50 prospects/week (Apollo or Lemlist fit better)","Highly regulated industries where cold outreach is restricted"}', 'One of the strongest multichannel outbound platforms in 2026 — pick it if you run a real SDR motion, skip it if you''re still validating a cold-outbound channel.', '{"https://help.reply.io/"}', 'Pricing scales fast — per-user multichannel and the AI SDR add-on can easily push a 5-rep team past $1,500/month before the contact database. Deliverability tooling is good but not magic; cold outreach to crap lists still tanks domain reputation regardless of warm-up. The AI SDR is impressive in demos but needs careful ICP tuning and human review on early sequences before you trust it solo. UI density is high — onboarding a non-technical SDR takes a week, not a day.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Launch a 7-touch multichannel outbound sequence (email + LinkedIn + call) to 500 prospects.","Run an AI SDR pilot booking discovery calls from a tightly-defined ICP without human intervention.","Warm up 5 new sending mailboxes across 3 domains before launching a high-volume campaign.","Sync replies and meetings booked into HubSpot deals with sequence attribution intact."}', 'Sweet spot: a B2B SaaS or services company with a defined ICP, a real outbound SDR motion (not just inbound + light prospecting), and 2–10 reps. Reply.io''s combination of multichannel orchestration plus deliverability plumbing plus the AI SDR option is genuinely best-in-class for that profile — it replaces 3–4 separate tools (sequencer, dialer, warm-up, AI copilot) with one stack.

Failure modes. The most common is using Reply.io to scale a broken outbound motion — bad ICP, wrong message, weak offer. The platform will efficiently send your bad message to more people and burn your sending domains in the process. The AI SDR amplifies this risk: if Jason is trained on a fuzzy ICP, you''ll book meetings with the wrong people at industrial volumes. Deliverability claims also depend heavily on list hygiene — buying contact lists and sending to them is a fast path to spam-folder purgatory regardless of warm-up.

What to pilot. Run a 30-day trial with one rep, one tightly-defined ICP segment of 200 prospects, and a 5-step multichannel sequence you''ve already validated manually. Measure replies, meetings booked, and deliverability (inbox placement) versus your current tool. If the unit economics make sense at one rep, the per-seat pricing scales linearly to the team. If the AI SDR is on your shortlist, run it in shadow mode (it drafts, you review and send) for two weeks before letting it act autonomously.', now()),
('Pipedrive', 'pipedrive', 'Sales-pipeline-first CRM with a built-in AI Sales Assistant that surfaces next-best actions per deal.', 'Pipedrive is a sales-led CRM founded in Estonia in 2010 and built around a single design opinion: the deal pipeline is the primary interface, not contacts or accounts. Reps see deals as cards in kanban columns by stage, drag them forward as they progress, and the rest of the CRM (contacts, activities, emails, notes) hangs off each deal card. This makes Pipedrive significantly easier for non-technical sales reps to adopt than Salesforce or HubSpot, which lead with database-style record views.

The 2024–2026 product layers an AI Sales Assistant throughout: it scores deals by close probability, flags stalled deals that need attention, suggests next-best actions per pipeline stage, drafts follow-up emails, and summarises long email threads attached to deals. Recent additions include AI-generated email composition, meeting prep summaries pulled from past activity, and AI-suggested workflows. Pipedrive also includes native add-ons for lead management (LeadBooster), web visitor tracking, project delivery (Projects), and document signing (Smart Docs).

Distribution runs through Impact (the affiliate network) and an in-house referral program. Pipedrive serves roughly 100,000+ paying customers — heavily concentrated in SMBs from 1 to 50 reps — and the product''s reputation is "the CRM your sales team will actually use." It is rarely the answer for enterprise RevOps but is consistently the right answer for growing SMBs.', 'https://www.pipedrive.com', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Essential","price":"$14/user/mo","features":["Pipeline management","Activity tracking","Email integration","2-way calendar sync"]},{"plan":"Advanced","price":"$29/user/mo","features":["Email open and click tracking","Workflow automation","AI Sales Assistant","Group emailing"]},{"plan":"Professional","price":"$59/user/mo","features":["AI email composer","Revenue forecasting","E-signatures","Custom reporting","Team management"]},{"plan":"Power / Enterprise","price":"$79–$129/user/mo","features":["Phone support","Unlimited custom fields","SSO","Security alerts","Dedicated account manager"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","mobile","api"}', '{"Visual kanban deal pipeline","AI Sales Assistant (deal scoring, next actions)","AI email composer and thread summariser","Workflow automation builder","Email integration with open and click tracking","Built-in calling and call recording","Web visitor tracking (LeadBooster add-on)","E-signatures (Smart Docs)","Revenue forecasting and reporting","Mobile apps (iOS and Android)","Custom fields and pipelines","Team activity dashboards"}', '{"Gmail","Outlook","Slack","Zapier","Make","Trello","Asana","QuickBooks","Xero","Mailchimp","Zoom","Microsoft Teams"}', true, '{"SMB sales teams (1–50 reps) wanting a CRM reps will actually use","Founders running founder-led sales who need pipeline discipline","Agencies tracking client deals across multiple accounts","B2B services companies with defined sales stages"}', '{"Enterprise RevOps teams needing complex object models (Salesforce wins)","Marketing-led orgs that want CRM + marketing automation in one (HubSpot fits better)","Pure transactional sales (ecommerce checkout doesn''t need a CRM)"}', 'The best SMB sales CRM in 2026 — pipeline-first design that reps adopt without complaint. Pick Pipedrive for sales-led teams under 50 reps; pick HubSpot or Salesforce above that.', '{"https://support.pipedrive.com/"}', 'Reporting and dashboards are functional but less powerful than Salesforce or HubSpot at the higher tiers — complex revenue ops setups outgrow Pipedrive eventually. Native marketing automation is weak; teams that want CRM + marketing in one tool should look at HubSpot. The AI Sales Assistant''s deal scoring is useful directionally but not a substitute for actual rep judgement on complex deals. Per-user pricing escalates fast at the Professional and Power tiers — a 20-rep team on Professional is $14K/year before add-ons.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Manage a 6-stage B2B sales pipeline with 200 active deals across 5 reps.","Use the AI Sales Assistant to surface stalled deals every Monday morning.","Automate follow-up sequences when a deal sits in a stage longer than 7 days.","Forecast quarterly revenue with weighted pipeline values across territories."}', 'Sweet spot: a 1–50 rep SMB sales team that has outgrown spreadsheets, doesn''t want to drown in Salesforce setup, and just needs reps to keep deals moving through stages. Pipedrive''s adoption rate is genuinely high because the visual pipeline matches how sales reps already think — drag the card forward, log the call, schedule the next activity. The AI Sales Assistant adds a useful "what should I do next" layer without burying it under config.

Failure modes. Buying Pipedrive when you actually need HubSpot — if your motion is marketing-led with heavy email nurture, lead scoring, and content automation, Pipedrive''s thin marketing side will frustrate you within a quarter. Buying Pipedrive when you actually need Salesforce — once you have RevOps, complex territory rules, custom objects beyond contacts/companies/deals, or 50+ reps with role-based permissions, Pipedrive''s data model starts feeling cramped. And the AI features are helpful but not transformative; treat them as nice-to-haves, not the buying reason.

What to pilot. Take the 14-day trial, import your last 90 days of deals (CSV), set up your real pipeline stages, and have one rep use Pipedrive as their daily driver for two weeks. If the rep is faster (more deals advanced, fewer dropped follow-ups) and stops complaining about CRM admin, roll it out. If the rep keeps reverting to spreadsheets, the issue is process discipline, not the tool — Pipedrive won''t fix it.', now()),
('Teachable', 'teachable', 'Online course platform with AI course-creation tools for creators, coaches, and educators.', 'Teachable is one of the original creator-focused course platforms (founded 2014, acquired by Hotmart in 2020) that lets independent educators, coaches, and subject-matter experts package what they know into paid courses, coaching products, digital downloads, and bundles. The platform handles the unsexy infrastructure — video hosting, student enrolment, payment processing (including EU VAT), affiliate management, certificates of completion, drip schedules, and student community — so creators can focus on the curriculum.

The 2024–2026 product line layers AI throughout course creation: an AI Curriculum Generator that proposes a full course outline from a topic and audience description, AI Lesson generators that produce lesson scripts and quizzes, an AI summary tool for long video lessons, and AI-driven student insights that flag at-risk learners. Teachable also offers Coaching products (1:1 and group), Communities (forum-style discussion spaces), and Digital Downloads as separate product types alongside courses.

Teachable''s position vs Thinkific (the closest competitor) is roughly: Teachable is stronger on payments and the international tax handling (Hotmart''s heritage), while Thinkific is stronger on community and customisation. Both are credible, and the choice usually comes down to feature priorities and the tier-pricing math. The PartnerStack-managed affiliate program is widely promoted in the creator-economy space.', 'https://teachable.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["1 course / 1 coaching / 1 download","Up to 10 students","Transaction fees apply","Basic features"]},{"plan":"Basic","price":"$59/mo","features":["5 products","No transaction fees","Drip content","Coupons","Custom domain"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$159/mo","features":["50 products","Advanced reports","Affiliate marketing","Graded quizzes","Course completion certificates"]},{"plan":"Pro+ / Business","price":"$249–$665/mo","features":["200+ products","Bulk student imports","Custom user roles","Priority support","Custom payment gateway"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"AI Curriculum Generator (full course outlines)","AI Lesson generator (scripts and quizzes)","Video hosting and player","Coaching products (1:1 and group)","Communities (discussion forums)","Digital downloads","Drip content scheduling","Built-in payments (international, EU VAT)","Affiliate program management","Certificates of completion","Student progress and engagement reports","Email and SMS marketing"}', '{"Stripe","PayPal","Mailchimp","ConvertKit","ActiveCampaign","Zapier","Google Analytics","Facebook Pixel","Calendly","Zoom"}', true, '{"Independent course creators monetising expertise","Coaches packaging methodologies into structured programs","Subject-matter experts launching their first paid course","Creators selling internationally who need EU VAT handling"}', '{"Enterprise corporate L&D (use Docebo / Cornerstone)","Free / open-access course publishers (use Moodle / open-edX)","Creators on tiny budgets who can''t justify the Basic tier transaction-free pricing"}', 'A solid creator-first course platform with strong international payment handling and useful AI course-builder features. Pick Teachable for the payments edge; pick Thinkific for the community edge.', '{"https://support.teachable.com/"}', 'The free tier carries transaction fees that eat into margins quickly — most serious creators jump straight to Basic. Customisation is more limited than Thinkific''s — heavy theme editing requires CSS or hiring a developer. AI course-builder output is a useful starting point but produces generic curricula without significant editing — don''t expect to ship the AI''s draft. Pricing tiers escalate steeply, and the Pro tier (where most professional creators land) is $159/month before add-ons.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Launch a paid 8-module video course with drip scheduling and a private community.","Sell coaching packages with built-in scheduling and recurring billing.","Run an affiliate program where students earn commissions referring new enrolments.","Sell internationally with EU VAT, GST, and currency conversion handled automatically."}', 'Sweet spot: an individual creator or small team launching their first paid course or coaching product, who wants the platform to handle payments and tax internationally and doesn''t want to learn a complex LMS. Teachable''s Hotmart-heritage payment infrastructure is a real advantage if a meaningful share of your students are outside the US — the EU VAT handling alone removes a major operational headache.

Failure modes. The biggest one is choosing Teachable over Thinkific without comparing — both platforms hit the same sweet spot, and the decision comes down to which feature priorities matter more (Teachable: payments and international; Thinkific: community and customisation). The other failure mode is treating the AI course generator as a finished product — it produces structurally reasonable outlines and lesson scripts, but the value of a paid course is the creator''s perspective, not the AI''s generic restatement.

What to pilot. Build the first module of your real course on Teachable (free tier or Basic), set up payments with a $1 test product, and run 5 friends or beta users through enrolment, payment, and lesson completion. If the platform feels right, the affiliate program, community, and AI tools layer on cleanly. Compare the same first-module build on Thinkific in parallel — most creators find one platform feels noticeably better within an hour.', now()),
('Thinkific', 'thinkific', 'Course, community, and coaching platform with AI assistants for creators and education businesses.', 'Thinkific is a Vancouver-founded course platform (2012, publicly traded since 2021) that competes head-to-head with Teachable in the creator-led course space. The product covers courses, memberships, communities, coaching sessions, and digital downloads under one platform, and is generally considered the more customisable of the two — site themes, page builders, and custom domain handling go deeper than Teachable''s equivalents.

The 2024–2026 product line includes Thinkific AI features: AI Course Outline generator from a topic + audience brief, AI quiz generator, AI video transcription and chapter generation, an AI Course Assistant that helps students navigate content, and AI-powered lesson summaries. Communities is a particular strength — Thinkific''s native community product (formerly a separate spin-off product called Thinkific Communities) supports spaces, events, members, and discussion in a more social-network-feeling layout than Teachable''s lighter forums.

Thinkific Plus is the enterprise tier, used by larger education businesses, associations, and corporate L&D teams that need SSO, advanced API access, and dedicated support. The PartnerStack-managed affiliate program is widely active across the creator-economy review ecosystem. Thinkific powers tens of thousands of creators globally and is one of the most stable, well-funded options in the category.', 'https://www.thinkific.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["1 course","1 community","Limited features","Thinkific branding"]},{"plan":"Basic","price":"$49/mo","features":["Unlimited courses","Custom domain","Coupons","Drip content","Email integrations"]},{"plan":"Start","price":"$99/mo","features":["Communities","Live lessons","Memberships and bundles","Advanced course building"]},{"plan":"Grow / Plus","price":"$199–Custom","features":["Advanced site customisation","Bulk enrolments","Single sign-on (Plus)","API and webhooks","Dedicated CSM (Plus)"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","mobile","api"}', '{"AI Course Outline generator","AI quiz and lesson summary generators","AI video transcription with chapters","Native community product (spaces, events, discussion)","Live lessons (Zoom integration)","Memberships and bundle pricing","Coaching products with scheduling","Custom site themes and page builder","Drip content scheduling","Course completion certificates","Mobile learning apps","API and webhooks (Grow / Plus)"}', '{"Stripe","PayPal","Zoom","Mailchimp","ConvertKit","ActiveCampaign","Zapier","Google Analytics","Facebook Pixel","Calendly","Shopify"}', true, '{"Creators who want a strong native community alongside courses","Education businesses building branded customer-academy sites","Coaches running cohort-based programs with live sessions","Mid-market education orgs needing SSO and API (Thinkific Plus)"}', '{"Enterprise corporate L&D needing SCORM / xAPI compliance","Creators who want zero customisation and just need to ship (Teachable is faster)","Free / open-access publishers (LMS like Moodle fits better)"}', 'A strong creator-led course platform with the best native community product in the category. Pick Thinkific when community matters; pick Teachable when international payments matter more.', '{"https://support.thinkific.com/"}', 'The free tier is genuinely usable but Thinkific branding and the 1-course limit push serious creators to Basic quickly. Communities is good but newer than long-established forums (Circle, Mighty Networks) — feature parity is close but not identical. AI generators produce reasonable starting drafts, not finished curricula. Plus pricing requires a sales conversation and is significantly more expensive than the public tiers, which can surprise creators scaling up. International payment and tax handling is solid but less seamless than Teachable''s Hotmart-backed setup.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run a cohort-based course with live Zoom lessons, drip content, and a private community.","Build a customer-academy for a SaaS product with SSO via Thinkific Plus.","Launch a hybrid membership combining on-demand courses, monthly live calls, and a community.","Sell a coaching package with integrated scheduling, payments, and student progress tracking."}', 'Sweet spot: a creator or education business that views community as a first-class feature, not an afterthought. If your offer is a cohort program, mastermind, or membership where students learn from each other as much as from the curriculum, Thinkific''s native community tooling is the reason to pick it over Teachable. The customisation depth also pays off for creators who care about brand presentation.

Failure modes. The biggest one is choosing Thinkific over Teachable without auditing your real needs — both platforms are excellent for the standard creator-course use case, and the differences only matter if you''re leaning into community (Thinkific wins) or international payments (Teachable wins). Another failure mode is buying Plus too early — the public tiers handle most creator businesses well into seven figures of annual revenue, and Plus is meaningfully more expensive without proportionate features for most users.

What to pilot. Build your first course module on the free tier, set up a community space, and run 10 beta students through both the lesson and the discussion experience. If the community engagement feels alive (replies, threads, member-to-member interaction), Thinkific''s native social layer is doing real work and the upgrade to Start is justified. If the community sits empty regardless of platform, the bottleneck is your audience and onboarding, not the tooling.', now()),
('Kajabi', 'kajabi', 'All-in-one platform for courses, coaching, communities, email, and funnels — with built-in AI Creator Hub.', 'Kajabi is the long-running all-in-one creator-business platform that lets coaches, course-creators, and digital-product sellers run their entire operation — site, courses, communities, email marketing, sales funnels, payments, and analytics — under a single subscription. The pitch since 2010 has been "stop stitching Teachable + ConvertKit + Kajabi + Stripe + Circle together"; in 2026 that pitch now also covers AI content production via the Creator Hub.

Creator Hub is a suite of six AI tools embedded across the product: course-outline generation, email drafting, transcription, translation, AI dubbing for video lessons, and a Creator Studio that takes a single long-form video (a webinar, coaching call, or course module) and automatically slices it into 40+ derivative content pieces — short clips, social posts, email sequences, and blog drafts. Every plan, including Basic, includes the AI tools by default rather than gating them behind an upsell.

In January 2026 Kajabi rolled out its first major pricing overhaul in nearly a decade — Basic, Growth, and Pro tiers replaced the older naming, with new content limits and revised payment-processing fees. The platform remains positioned at the premium end of the creator-economy stack: it is materially more expensive than Teachable or Thinkific, but the business case is the saved subscription stack and the unified analytics view across products, marketing, and customers.', 'https://kajabi.com', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Basic","price":"$143/mo annual ($179 monthly)","features":["3 products","3 funnels","10K contacts","1 admin","All AI Creator Hub tools"]},{"plan":"Growth","price":"$199/mo annual ($249 monthly)","features":["15 products","15 funnels","25K contacts","10 admins","Advanced automations","Affiliate program"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$399/mo annual ($499 monthly)","features":["100 products","100 funnels","100K contacts","25 admins","Code editor","3 sites"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","mobile","api"}', '{"Online courses with video hosting and drip schedules","Coaching product type with 1:1 and group sessions","Communities with feeds, posts, and member directories","Email marketing with automations and broadcasts","Sales funnels and checkout pages","AI Creator Hub (outlines, emails, transcription, dubbing)","Creator Studio video repurposing (1 video to 40+ assets)","Native mobile apps (iOS and Android)","Built-in payments via Stripe and PayPal","Affiliate program (Growth and Pro tiers)","Page builder with templates","Analytics dashboard across products and marketing"}', '{"Stripe","PayPal","Zapier","Google Analytics","Mailchimp","ConvertKit","ActiveCampaign","Calendly","Zoom"}', true, '{"Coaches and consultants running paid programs end-to-end","Course creators consolidating off a multi-tool stack","Digital-product entrepreneurs at $10K-$500K/year revenue","Established creators who want one bill instead of seven"}', '{"Brand-new creators with no audience or revenue (price hurts pre-PMF)","Buyers who only need a course platform (Teachable / Thinkific are cheaper)","Teams that need a true LMS with SCORM / xAPI compliance"}', 'The premium all-in-one creator platform — pick it once your business has revenue and your tool sprawl hurts more than the subscription does.', '{"https://help.kajabi.com/"}', 'Pricing is materially higher than single-purpose alternatives — Basic at $179/mo is more than Teachable + ConvertKit combined for many starting creators. Page builder is capable but not as design-flexible as dedicated tools like Webflow or Leadpages. Email deliverability is fine but lags dedicated ESPs like ConvertKit at scale. The January 2026 pricing change introduced new payment-processing fees that some long-term users felt blindsided by — model the all-in cost carefully before migrating.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run a complete coaching business — site, course, community, emails, payments — under one login.","Repurpose one weekly webinar into 40+ social, email, and blog assets via Creator Studio.","Migrate off a Teachable + ConvertKit + Circle + Stripe stack to consolidate billing.","Launch a high-ticket cohort program with checkout, drip content, and member community."}', 'Sweet spot: an established coach, course-creator, or digital-product entrepreneur doing $10K-$500K/year who is currently paying for 5-7 separate tools and feeling the integration tax. Kajabi at $200-400/month replaces a stack that often runs $400-800/month at that revenue band, and the unified analytics across product, marketing, and customer is genuinely useful for figuring out which funnel is paying for the rest.

Failure modes. Pre-PMF creators with no audience get crushed by the price — Kajabi punishes you for showing up before you have revenue. Buyers who only need one of the seven things (just a course platform, just an email tool) overpay massively versus a focused tool. The 2026 pricing change introduced new payment-processing fees that compound monthly cost; model the all-in number, not just the headline plan price. Email deliverability is competent but not best-in-class — heavy email-driven businesses still want ConvertKit or Klaviyo.

What to pilot. List every tool in your current stack and total their monthly cost. If the number is above $300/month and at least 4 of those tools are things Kajabi natively replaces, the migration math probably works — run a 14-day trial, rebuild one funnel end-to-end, and compare the unified analytics view against your current Frankenstein dashboard. If the number is under $200/month, stay on focused tools longer.', now()),
('Skool', 'skool', 'Community + courses platform popularized by Alex Hormozi — one feed, simple courses, gamification baked in.', 'Skool is a community-and-courses platform that became the dominant brand in the creator-community space through 2023-2025, driven heavily by promotion from Alex Hormozi (who is a Skool investor and the platform''s most visible advocate). The product is deliberately opinionated and minimal: one private Facebook-group-style feed for posts and discussion, an unlimited number of courses with a clean lesson structure, gamified points and levels to drive engagement, an events calendar in members'' local time zones, native iOS/Android apps, and built-in subscription billing.

The simplicity is the selling point. Where Circle, Mighty Networks, and Kajabi let you architect rooms, channels, sub-spaces, and complex membership tiers, Skool gives you exactly one community feed and one course library — so members can never get lost, and creators can never over-engineer. The flat $99/month Pro tier (or $9/month Hobby for testing) means there is no pricing-tier complexity either: one plan, unlimited courses inside one community, unlimited members, and a 2.9% transaction fee on paid memberships.

What Skool deliberately does not do is what defines it. No quizzes, no certificates, no advanced LMS reporting, no email automation, no native CRM integrations, no custom roles beyond admin/member. If you need those, you are not the customer. If you want a single product that gets a paid community + course business shipped this week without integration work, Skool is the fastest path in 2026.', 'https://www.skool.com', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Hobby","price":"$9/mo","features":["1 admin","10% transaction fee","All core features","14-day trial"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$99/mo","features":["Unlimited admins","2.9% transaction fee","Custom URL","Unlimited courses","Unlimited members"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web","mobile"}', '{"Single private community feed (Facebook-group-style)","Unlimited courses inside a single community","Native video hosting (no Vimeo / Loom needed)","Gamification with points and levels","Events calendar with local timezone support","Built-in subscription billing and recurring payments","Native iOS and Android apps with push notifications","Mobile-first member experience","Member directory","Discovery via Skool Games and public community listing"}', '{"Stripe","Zapier (limited)","YouTube (embed)","Loom (embed)","Custom domain"}', true, '{"Coaches and creators launching their first paid community","Influencers monetizing an audience with one paid tier","Niche-expert teachers running cohort-based courses","Mastermind operators who want simplicity over feature depth"}', '{"Teams needing advanced LMS features (quizzes, certificates, SCORM)","Email-marketing-heavy businesses (no native ESP)","Communities needing complex roles, sub-spaces, or workflow automation"}', 'The fastest path to a paid community + course business in 2026 — radical simplicity is the feature.', '{"https://help.skool.com/"}', 'No quizzes, certificates, or advanced LMS reporting — disqualifies serious accreditation use cases. No email marketing or automation tools — you must connect Mailchimp / ConvertKit externally and miss the unified contact view. Native integrations are very limited; Zapier covers most needs but adds latency. The single-feed model that''s a feature for some communities is a constraint for others — if you need separate spaces for different cohorts or topics, Skool will fight you. Discovery tools (Skool Games leaderboard) drive traffic but also concentrate attention on already-large communities.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Launch a $49/month paid community with a built-in course in under an hour.","Run a 12-week cohort-based course with daily community discussion and live events.","Move a free Facebook Group of 5,000 members into a paid Skool community.","Build a high-ticket mastermind ($497-$2K/month) with a single feed and curated content."}', 'Sweet spot: a coach, creator, or expert who has an audience and wants to launch a paid community + course in days, not months. Skool''s opinionated simplicity is the product — you cannot over-engineer it because there are no levers to over-engineer. The Hormozi association also drives discovery; Skool Games and the public community listings genuinely funnel new members to communities that ship engagement.

Failure modes. The most common mistake is buying Skool when your business needs LMS depth — quizzes, certificates, compliance reporting — and trying to bolt those on. You will fail; switch to Thinkific or Kajabi. The second failure is treating it as an email platform — it isn''t one, and trying to drive your business off Skool''s notification system instead of a real ESP will hit deliverability walls. Third, a community that needs separate sub-spaces (multiple cohorts running in parallel, different content for different tiers) will fight the single-feed model.

What to pilot. Start a Skool community on the $9 Hobby plan for two weeks. Onboard 10 real members from your audience, post daily, run one live event, and ship one course module. If engagement feels alive and you want to charge for it, switch to Pro and set a price. If onboarding 10 members already exposed structural limits (you wished for sub-channels, automation, or quizzes within the first week), Skool is the wrong tool and Circle is the next look.', now()),
('Circle', 'circle-so', 'Modern community platform with rich spaces, workflows, and AI agents at the Plus tier.', 'Circle is a community platform aimed at creators, coaches, and brands who want a fully-branded community without the engineering work of building one. Where Skool is deliberately minimal, Circle is deliberately structured: spaces (think channels), groups (think folders of spaces), member directories, paywalls, events, courses, livestreams, and a workflow engine for automating member journeys (welcome sequences, drip content, role assignment, tagging). The 2026 product also includes Circle AI — agents that can answer member questions from your knowledge base, summarize discussions, and run lightweight moderation tasks.

Pricing is tiered around community size and feature depth: Professional ($89/mo annual) for course creators and small memberships, Business ($199/mo annual) for growing communities needing workflows and automation, Enterprise ($419/mo annual) for AI features and larger communities, and Circle Plus (custom pricing) which replaces the old top tier and bundles AI Agents, AI workflows, custom SSO, the lowest transaction fees, a headless member API, and branded mobile app options. Email Hub is a $99/mo add-on with 10K contacts, broadcasts, forms, and automations.

Circle''s differentiator versus Skool is sophistication: rich spaces, real workflow automation, branded mobile apps (on Plus), and a real API. The cost is complexity — Circle communities can sprawl and confuse new members if not architected carefully — and price, since transaction fees stack on top of Stripe''s standard cut.', 'https://circle.so', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Professional","price":"$89/mo annual ($129 monthly)","features":["Unlimited members","Spaces and groups","Live streams","2% transaction fee","Course module"]},{"plan":"Business","price":"$199/mo annual ($219 monthly)","features":["Workflows and automations","Custom branding","API access","1% transaction fee","Member tags"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"$419/mo annual","features":["AI features","Activity scores","Advanced analytics","Priority support"]},{"plan":"Circle Plus","price":"Custom","features":["AI Agents","AI workflows","Custom SSO","0.5% fees","Branded iOS / Android apps","Headless member API","Dedicated CSM"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","mobile","api"}', '{"Spaces (channels) and groups (folders of spaces)","Member directories with profiles and search","Workflow engine for automation","Built-in courses with video hosting","Live streams and events","Paywalls and recurring memberships","Circle AI agents (Plus tier)","AI workflows and discussion summaries","Email Hub add-on (broadcasts, forms, automations)","Branded iOS and Android apps (Plus tier)","Headless member API","Custom SSO and admin controls"}', '{"Stripe","Zapier","Mailchimp","ConvertKit","Make","Webhooks","Slack","Discord","Custom SSO providers"}', true, '{"Mid-to-large paid communities needing structure and automation","Brands hosting customer / fan communities at scale","Course creators wanting a richer member experience than Skool","Enterprise customer-success teams running help communities"}', '{"Solo creators launching their first paid community (Skool is faster)","Buyers on tight budgets — transaction fees compound quickly","Teams that just need a Slack-replacement for internal team chat"}', 'The most feature-complete branded community platform in 2026 — pick it when Skool''s simplicity becomes a constraint and you need real workflow automation.', '{"https://help.circle.so/"}', 'Pricing climbs fast — Business at $199/mo is realistically the floor for most growing communities, and transaction fees (2% / 1% / 0.5%) stack on top of Stripe''s 2.9% + $0.30, producing real all-in costs of 3.4-4.9% per transaction. AI Agents are gated behind Circle Plus (custom enterprise pricing), so smaller communities can''t use them. Email Hub is a separate $99/mo add-on rather than included. The richer feature set means new members can get lost if community architecture is sloppy — onboarding flows need real design.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Migrate a 5,000-member community off Facebook Groups onto a fully-branded paid platform.","Run a customer community with role-based access, automation workflows, and member tagging.","Build a multi-cohort coaching program with separate spaces per cohort and shared resources.","Deploy AI Agents to answer common member questions from a knowledge base 24/7."}', 'Sweet spot: a creator, brand, or company past the "first paid community" stage that has 500+ members, multiple cohorts or content streams, and is feeling Skool''s single-feed constraint. Circle''s spaces, workflows, and member-tagging give you the architecture to run a complex community without building it from scratch — and the Plus tier''s AI Agents and headless API turn it into a real platform you can integrate with the rest of your stack.

Failure modes. First-time community operators often pick Circle when they should pick Skool — the feature surface gives them too many decisions before they''ve learned what their members actually need. Transaction fees stack: a community doing $20K/month in memberships pays $400-$1,000/month in Circle + Stripe fees alone, on top of the subscription. AI Agents are real but live behind Circle Plus enterprise pricing — smaller communities can''t access them yet. Sprawling space architectures cause new-member confusion; mitigate with a strict 5-space cap and one onboarding workflow.

What to pilot. If you already have a community on another platform, pick 50 active members and rebuild your top 3 spaces in Circle on the Business tier for 30 days. Measure two things: weekly active members and average post depth. If both improve versus your previous platform, the migration math works. If they don''t, the bottleneck is your content and community management, not the tool — and Circle''s extra features won''t fix that.', now()),
('Leadpages', 'leadpages', 'Landing-page builder with a built-in AI Engine that drafts a branded page from a single text prompt.', 'Leadpages is one of the original landing-page builders (founded 2012) and remains a default pick for small businesses, solopreneurs, and lead-gen-focused marketers who need conversion-optimized pages without hiring a designer. The 2026 product wraps the long-standing template library and drag-and-drop editor with an AI Engine that generates a fully-branded landing page in roughly 60 seconds from a text prompt — applying your Brand Kit colors, fonts, and voice automatically — plus AI-powered URL imports and an AI chat assistant for in-editor editing.

The platform covers the full lead-gen workflow: unlimited landing pages and pop-ups, lead magnets and gated content, A/B testing on every plan, custom domains with SSL, dynamic text replacement, lead enrichment, and integrations with the major email and CRM tools. The Optimize tier ($199/mo) adds Smart Traffic — Leadpages'' AI visitor-routing feature that automatically sends each visitor to the variant most likely to convert for them — plus heatmaps, auto-personalization, and 1,000-page limits. Scale ($399/mo) targets agencies and multi-brand operations.

Pricing in 2026 starts at Grow ($99/mo, $79/mo annual) and includes monthly AI credits on every plan (40K Grow / 80K Optimize / 160K Scale) that power page creation, URL imports, and AI chat. Top-up packs from $2.50 cover overages. Every plan includes unlimited traffic, A/B testing, and custom domains with SSL — no traffic-based pricing surprises.', 'https://www.leadpages.com', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Grow","price":"$79/mo annual ($99 monthly)","features":["500 pages","Manual A/B testing","40K AI credits/mo","Dynamic text replacement","Lead enrichment"]},{"plan":"Optimize","price":"$159/mo annual ($199 monthly)","features":["1,000 pages","Smart Traffic AI routing","80K AI credits","Heatmaps","Auto-personalization","24-month analytics"]},{"plan":"Scale","price":"$319/mo annual ($399 monthly)","features":["Multi-brand workspaces","160K AI credits","Agency features","Priority support"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"AI Engine: prompt-to-page in ~60 seconds with Brand Kit","Drag-and-drop landing-page editor","200+ conversion-optimized templates","Pop-ups and alert bars","A/B testing on every plan","Smart Traffic AI visitor routing (Optimize+)","Click and scroll heatmaps (Optimize+)","Dynamic text replacement","Lead enrichment","Unlimited traffic on every plan","Custom domains with SSL","Pre-built conversion tools (countdowns, opt-in flows)"}', '{"Mailchimp","ConvertKit","ActiveCampaign","HubSpot","Salesforce","Zapier","Stripe","Google Analytics","Facebook Pixel","Webhooks"}', true, '{"Solopreneurs running paid ads to lead-gen pages","Small businesses needing fast landing pages without a designer","Coaches and consultants capturing leads for offers","Affiliate marketers spinning up campaign-specific pages"}', '{"Enterprise teams needing AdMap-style ad-to-page personalization (Instapage wins)","Webflow / Framer users who want full-site design control","SEO content sites (Leadpages is built for conversion, not content depth)"}', 'The most polished mid-market landing-page builder in 2026 with the cleanest AI page-creation flow at the price point.', '{"https://docs.leadpages.com/"}', 'AI Engine output is good for first drafts but still needs human editing for genuinely on-brand pages — treat it as a starting point. Smart Traffic only kicks in after meaningful traffic volume, so smaller campaigns won''t see its value. Editor flexibility is below Webflow / Unbounce — power designers will hit ceilings on custom layouts. AI credit caps can bite heavy users; budget for top-ups. Scale tier feels expensive relative to peers for what it adds beyond Optimize.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Spin up a campaign-specific landing page in under 10 minutes from an AI prompt.","A/B test five variants of a webinar registration page with Smart Traffic auto-routing.","Build a 30-page library of lead magnets and opt-in pages without hiring a designer.","Run a Facebook ad campaign with personalized landing-page variants per audience segment."}', 'Sweet spot: a small-to-mid-sized business or solopreneur running paid traffic (Facebook, Google, LinkedIn) to lead-gen pages who needs to ship 5-30 landing pages a quarter without a designer on staff. Leadpages'' AI Engine collapses the "brief a designer, wait a week, iterate" loop into a 60-second prompt, and Smart Traffic is genuinely useful once you have enough volume to feed it.

Failure modes. The AI Engine is a productivity tool, not a designer replacement — pages that ship without human editing look templated, and templated pages convert worse than custom ones over time. Smart Traffic needs traffic volume to learn; campaigns under 1,000 visitors per variant won''t see meaningful uplift. Power designers who already use Webflow or Framer will find Leadpages'' editor constraining. And while pricing is fair for the value, the Scale tier''s jump to $399/mo is hard to justify for most non-agency use cases.

What to pilot. Take your three highest-spend ad campaigns. Build the landing pages in Leadpages using the AI Engine, run them against your current pages for 14 days, and measure conversion rate and cost per lead. If the AI-built pages match or beat your current pages and you saved 80% of the design time, the $99/mo tier is the cheapest design hire you''ll ever make. If the AI pages underperform, you have two options: edit them harder (which still saves time) or accept that your category needs custom design.', now()),
('Instapage', 'instapage', 'Enterprise landing-page platform with AdMap, AI personalization, and the deepest ad-to-page workflow on the market.', 'Instapage is the premium, enterprise-end landing-page platform — positioned squarely at performance-marketing teams running serious paid-ad spend (Google Ads, Meta, LinkedIn, programmatic) where the cost of a poorly-matched landing page is measured in thousands of dollars per day in wasted spend. Where Leadpages serves SMBs and solopreneurs at $99-399/mo, Instapage starts at $79/mo annual (Create) and climbs into custom Convert pricing for enterprise customers, with a feature set built around scale, security, and ad-to-page workflows.

The standout feature is AdMap: a visual canvas that shows the connection between every ad campaign / ad group / ad and its corresponding landing page. Marketers running 100+ ads can see at a glance which ads point to which pages, track per-connection conversion data, and build personalized variants per ad group without a single line of code. Personalization extends beyond AdMap — Instapage variants can swap content based on UTM parameters, geolocation, device, or any URL parameter, which is the toolset performance marketers need to push conversion rates above industry baselines.

The 2026 product also includes AI page generation, AI-powered content blocks, A/B testing, click and scroll heatmaps, server-side experimentation, and integrations across the entire ad-tech and martech stack. Instapage is the right choice precisely when ad-to-page personalization is the bottleneck — and overkill if it isn''t.', 'https://instapage.com', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Create","price":"$79/mo annual ($99 monthly)","features":["Up to 15K visitors/mo","Unlimited landing pages","AI page generation","Drag-and-drop editor","30+ integrations"]},{"plan":"Optimize","price":"$199-$299/mo","features":["30K-50K visitors","AdMap","Personalization","A/B testing","Heatmaps","AI experiments"]},{"plan":"Convert","price":"Custom","features":["Custom traffic","SSO","Audit logs","Migration support","Dedicated CSM","SLA"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"AdMap visual ad-to-page connection canvas","AI-powered page generation","Personalization by UTM, geo, device, and URL param","A/B testing with statistical significance","Click and scroll heatmaps","Server-side experimentation","AMP page support for mobile","Drag-and-drop editor with global blocks","Form builder with conditional logic","Dynamic text replacement","Custom domains and SSL","Enterprise SSO and audit logs (Convert)"}', '{"Google Ads","Meta Ads","LinkedIn Ads","HubSpot","Salesforce","Marketo","Zapier","Google Analytics","Segment","Webhooks","Mailchimp","ActiveCampaign"}', true, '{"Performance marketers running $50K+/mo in paid ad spend","Agencies managing complex multi-client ad campaigns","B2B SaaS marketing teams running ad-to-demo funnels","Enterprises needing SSO, audit logs, and security review"}', '{"Solopreneurs and small businesses (Leadpages is cheaper and sufficient)","Content / SEO sites (this is built for paid traffic, not organic)","Teams without enough ad volume to justify AdMap (under ~20 active ads)"}', 'The premium landing-page platform for serious performance marketers — pick it when ad-to-page personalization at scale is your conversion bottleneck.', '{"https://help.instapage.com/"}', 'Pricing is materially higher than Leadpages and Unbounce at the same feature depth — Optimize starts at $199/mo and the real value features (full AdMap, advanced personalization, server-side experiments) live at the upper tiers. Visitor-based pricing means traffic spikes can push you into a higher tier mid-month. Editor learning curve is steeper than Leadpages — onboarding a new team member takes a week, not a day. Migrations off Instapage are painful; the platform locks you in via deeply-integrated AdMap workflows.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Map 200 Google Ads ad groups to personalized landing pages via AdMap and track per-ad conversion.","Run a B2B SaaS ad-to-demo funnel with personalization by company size and industry.","A/B test landing-page variants with server-side experimentation for accurate stats.","Spin up an agency-side workflow managing 25 client accounts with shared assets and per-client analytics."}', 'Sweet spot: a performance-marketing team or agency spending $50K+/month on paid ads, running 50+ active ad groups, and bottlenecked on landing-page personalization. AdMap is genuinely the best ad-to-page workflow on the market — for teams that need it, the productivity gain pays for the platform within a quarter. Personalization by UTM / geo / device adds another 10-30% on conversion rates for funnels with diverse traffic sources.

Failure modes. The two most common mistakes are (1) buying Instapage when Leadpages would suffice — small businesses with 5-10 active ads and a single landing page get no AdMap value and overpay 2-3x — and (2) signing up for Optimize at $199/mo and never actually using AdMap or personalization, which turns Instapage into a very expensive Unbounce. Visitor-based pricing surprises teams whose traffic spikes mid-month. And the platform lock-in is real — once your AdMap is built, migrating off requires recreating the entire ad-to-page architecture.

What to pilot. If you''re spending under $20K/month on paid ads or running fewer than 20 active ad groups, skip Instapage and use Leadpages or Unbounce. If you''re above that threshold, run a 14-day Optimize trial focused entirely on AdMap: connect your top campaign, build personalized variants per top-3 ad groups, and measure conversion-rate lift. If the lift exceeds 15% on your top campaign, the math works. If it doesn''t, your bottleneck isn''t the landing page — it''s upstream in targeting or downstream in your offer.', now()),
('Carrd', 'carrd', 'Dead-simple single-page site builder by AJ — one-page sites, landing pages, and link-in-bios at unbeatable price.', 'Carrd is a one-person product built by AJ since 2016 that does exactly one thing extraordinarily well: simple, responsive, single-page websites. Pick a template, edit the content inline, point a domain at it, and you''re live. The interface is the antithesis of Webflow / Framer complexity — no CMS, no animations panel, no breakpoint editor — just a clean drag-of-blocks experience that a non-designer can finish in 30 minutes.

The product covers the long tail of "I just need a page" use cases: personal portfolios, link-in-bio pages, event landing pages, product coming-soon pages, single-product launches, freelancer one-pagers, and resume sites. Pro tiers add forms (with Mailchimp / ConvertKit / Google Sheets integration), Google Analytics, custom domains, password protection, A/B testing, widgets (Stripe, Calendly, YouTube, etc.), and the ability to remove Carrd branding.

Carrd''s position in 2026 is the price-per-site champion: a single Pro Standard plan at $19/year covers up to 10 sites with custom domains. For makers, indie hackers, and anyone who launches multiple small projects, the unit economics are unbeatable. AJ has stayed solo and the product has stayed focused — no scope creep into multi-page CMS territory, no enterprise pivot.', 'https://carrd.co', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["3 sites","Carrd subdomain","Basic templates","Limited features"]},{"plan":"Pro Lite","price":"$9/yr","features":["Custom domain","No Carrd branding","Up to 3 sites","Forms"]},{"plan":"Pro Standard","price":"$19/yr","features":["Up to 10 sites","All widgets","Forms with integrations","Google Analytics"]},{"plan":"Pro Plus","price":"$49/yr","features":["Up to 25 sites","A/B testing","Password protection","Embed code"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web"}', '{"Drag-and-block single-page editor","100+ responsive templates","Custom domain support","Forms with Mailchimp / ConvertKit / Google Sheets","Stripe payment widget","Calendly, YouTube, Google Maps embeds","Google Analytics integration","Password-protected pages","A/B testing (Pro Plus)","Mobile-responsive by default","SEO meta editor"}', '{"Mailchimp","ConvertKit","Google Sheets","Stripe","Calendly","YouTube","Google Analytics","Zapier"}', true, '{"Indie hackers shipping product landing pages","Freelancers building portfolio one-pagers","Event organisers needing a quick landing page","Makers running link-in-bio pages for social"}', '{"Multi-page sites with a CMS or blog","Teams needing collaboration / version history","Anyone needing animations or complex interactions"}', 'The cheapest, fastest way to ship a single-page site in 2026 — pick it for one-pagers, skip it for anything bigger.', '{"https://docs.carrd.co/"}', 'Single-page only by design — if you need multi-page navigation, a blog, or a CMS, Carrd is the wrong tool and Webflow / Framer / WordPress fit better. Animation and interaction options are minimal — pages are static by design. The editor is desktop-only and not optimised for mobile editing. AJ is solo, so support is email-only and feature velocity is deliberate rather than fast.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Ship a product coming-soon landing page in under an hour with a waitlist form.","Build a link-in-bio page with custom domain for social-media profiles.","Create a one-page personal portfolio with contact form for freelancing.","Launch an event landing page with RSVP form integrated to Google Sheets."}', 'Sweet spot: an indie hacker, freelancer, or maker who launches multiple small projects per year and wants each one to have a clean, professional landing page without spending hours in Webflow. At $19/year for 10 sites, Carrd is essentially free per project — the only AI / no-code tool where the unit economics actually feel generous rather than predatory.

Failure modes. The constraint is the feature: people try to force Carrd into multi-page territory by stacking sections vertically and end up with a 6,000px-tall page that performs badly on mobile. If your project has genuine multi-page needs (blog, docs, product catalogue), use a real CMS. The other failure mode is treating Carrd as a long-term home for a growing business — at some point you outgrow it and migration to Webflow / Framer is non-trivial because Carrd doesn''t export clean HTML/CSS.

What to pilot. Build your next side-project landing page in Carrd in 60 minutes. If the page ships, looks professional, and converts as well as your previous Webflow effort, the $19/year subscription pays for itself the first time you launch a second project. If you find yourself fighting the editor for animations or multi-page structure, your project is too big for Carrd and you should pick a different tool from the start.', now()),
('Systeme.io', 'systeme-io', 'All-in-one funnel, email, course, and affiliate platform — French solo-founder business with a generous free tier.', 'Systeme.io is an all-in-one online-business platform built by French founder Aurelien Amacker that bundles funnels, email marketing, courses, membership sites, blogs, automation, and an affiliate program into one tool. The pitch is straightforward: instead of stitching together ClickFunnels + ActiveCampaign + Teachable + ThriveCart + Tapfiliate (often $300+/mo combined), you get all of it for $0–$97/month, with a generous free tier that supports up to 2,000 contacts and unlimited emails.

The product covers the full digital-product creator stack: drag-and-drop sales funnels, email broadcasts and automation sequences, online course hosting with drip lessons, membership-site gating, an evergreen webinar feature, a built-in affiliate program where you set commissions and Systeme handles tracking + payouts, blog hosting, and one-click upsells / order bumps. Integrations cover Stripe, PayPal, Zapier, and a small but growing native-integration list.

Systeme.io grew rapidly as a ClickFunnels alternative through 2022–2025, particularly in European, Latin American, and emerging-market creator communities where ClickFunnels'' $147/mo entry price was prohibitive. Auchan-funded backing gives the business runway, but Aurelien still runs it as an unusually lean operation — the product''s breadth-to-headcount ratio is one of the best in SaaS.', 'https://systeme.io', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["2,000 contacts","Unlimited emails","3 funnels","1 course","Affiliate program"]},{"plan":"Startup","price":"$27/mo","features":["5,000 contacts","10 funnels","5 courses","Custom domain"]},{"plan":"Webinar","price":"$47/mo","features":["10,000 contacts","50 funnels","20 courses","Evergreen webinars"]},{"plan":"Unlimited","price":"$97/mo","features":["Unlimited contacts","Unlimited funnels","Unlimited courses","Priority support"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Drag-and-drop sales funnel builder","Email broadcasts and automation sequences","Online course hosting with drip content","Membership site gating","Evergreen webinar hosting","Built-in affiliate program with tracking and payouts","Blog hosting","One-click upsells and order bumps","Stripe and PayPal payment integration","A/B testing on funnel pages","Tag-based contact segmentation"}', '{"Stripe","PayPal","Zapier","Google Analytics","Facebook Pixel","Mailgun","SendGrid"}', true, '{"Solopreneurs launching their first online course or coaching offer","Creators running affiliate-driven product launches","Coaches selling memberships and digital products","Bootstrapped founders avoiding the ClickFunnels stack price"}', '{"Enterprise teams needing SOC2, SSO, and advanced compliance","Sophisticated marketers wanting best-in-class email deliverability (use ConvertKit / Customer.io)","High-volume e-commerce with complex catalogues (Shopify wins)"}', 'The best all-in-one bargain in the creator stack — generous free tier, unbeatable price, but each module is "good enough" rather than best-in-class.', '{"https://help.systeme.io/"}', 'Each individual module is competent but not best-in-class — email deliverability lags behind dedicated ESPs, the page builder is less flexible than Webflow / Unbounce, and the course module lacks the depth of Teachable / Kajabi. Native integrations are limited compared to the major standalone tools, so Zapier is often the bridge. Customer support is responsive but largely text-based; phone / live chat is limited. The UI feels dense compared to single-purpose tools, with a learning curve to find features.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Launch an online course with funnel, email automation, and affiliate program in one weekend.","Run an evergreen webinar funnel selling a high-ticket coaching offer.","Build a membership site with drip-released content and recurring billing.","Replace a ClickFunnels + ActiveCampaign + Tapfiliate stack with one $27/mo subscription."}', 'Sweet spot: a solo creator or small coaching business launching their first or second digital product who would otherwise spend 3–6 months stitching together a ClickFunnels + ActiveCampaign + Teachable + Tapfiliate stack. Systeme.io collapses that integration work into a weekend and a $27/mo subscription, which is the difference between launching and not launching for many bootstrapped creators.

Failure modes. The "all-in-one" tradeoff is real — if email deliverability matters more than anything (you sell to enterprise buyers, you have a 100K+ list), a dedicated ESP like ConvertKit or Customer.io will outperform. The page builder is enough for funnels but not for a brand site that needs Webflow-level design control. Power users sometimes hit ceilings on automation logic that Zapier can fill but that adds complexity back in. The breadth means each tab in the dashboard is shallower than the standalone product would be.

What to pilot. Pick one digital-product launch — a course, a coaching offer, or a small SaaS waitlist — and build the entire funnel (landing page, email sequence, checkout, post-purchase upsell, affiliate link) in Systeme.io''s free tier. If the launch ships, the conversion math works, and you didn''t hit a feature wall, upgrade to Startup at $27/mo and replace your existing tools one at a time. If you hit deliverability or design ceilings within the first launch, your business is past Systeme.io''s sweet spot.', now()),
('Calendly', 'calendly', 'The default scheduling platform — round-robin, team scheduling, and a growing AI scheduling assistant layer.', 'Calendly is the dominant scheduling platform globally, used by tens of millions of professionals to eliminate the back-and-forth of finding a meeting time. Share a link, the recipient picks an available slot from your calendar, the meeting is booked with the right buffer, video link, and reminders — done. The product expanded from solo-professional scheduling into team scheduling (round-robin, collective, group), routing forms (qualify leads before booking), and embedded scheduling for SaaS apps and websites.

The 2024–2026 expansion has focused heavily on AI: Cal, Calendly''s scheduling assistant, can read inbound emails, propose times, hold tentative slots, and confirm meetings without the user manually sending availability. The product also added meeting workflows (auto-send pre-meeting questionnaires, post-meeting follow-ups), Salesforce / HubSpot integration depth, and analytics on team scheduling load. The Routing product has become a serious competitor to Chili Piper for inbound lead routing in B2B sales.

Calendly is the default — every salesperson, recruiter, consultant, and coach has used or seen it. The brand has shifted from "free scheduling tool" to "scheduling automation platform for revenue teams," with pricing tiers reflecting the move upmarket. The free tier remains generous enough for individual professionals, but real value lives in the Teams and Enterprise tiers.', 'https://calendly.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["1 event type","Unlimited meetings","Calendar integration","Calendly branding"]},{"plan":"Standard","price":"$10/seat/mo","features":["Unlimited event types","Multiple calendars","Workflows","No branding"]},{"plan":"Teams","price":"$16/seat/mo","features":["Round-robin","Routing","Salesforce sync","Meeting polls"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["SSO","SCIM","Advanced security","Dedicated CSM"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","mobile","api"}', '{"Calendar-aware scheduling links","Round-robin team scheduling","Routing forms for inbound lead qualification","Cal AI scheduling assistant (email-driven)","Workflow automations (reminders, follow-ups)","Embedded scheduling widget for websites","Meeting polls and group scheduling","Salesforce and HubSpot bi-directional sync","Zoom / Google Meet / Teams auto-link","Buffers, padding, and daily limit controls","Analytics dashboard for team load"}', '{"Google Calendar","Outlook","Office 365","Salesforce","HubSpot","Zoom","Google Meet","Microsoft Teams","Stripe","PayPal","Zapier","Slack"}', true, '{"Salespeople running outbound and inbound discovery calls","Recruiters scheduling candidate interviews at scale","Consultants and coaches selling time-based services","SaaS teams embedding scheduling in their product"}', '{"Engineering teams wanting open-source / self-hosted (Cal.com fits)","Solo users who only book a meeting a month (overkill)","Highly customised booking flows requiring deep API control"}', 'The category default — pick it for reliability and integration depth, switch to Cal.com if you want open-source or aggressive AI-first features.', '{"https://help.calendly.com/"}', 'Pricing has crept upmarket — what used to be a $10 individual tool is now a $16/seat team product, and serious revenue-team features sit in Enterprise pricing that requires sales contact. The Cal AI assistant is good but not as fully autonomous as marketing suggests; it still requires human review on ambiguous emails. Routing forms are powerful but require setup expertise to do well — most teams under-use them. The free tier''s 1-event-type limit is restrictive enough to feel like a downgrade vs. competitors'' free tiers.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Share a personal scheduling link that respects multiple connected calendars.","Run round-robin lead distribution across an SDR team with HubSpot sync.","Embed a scheduling widget on a SaaS pricing page for sales-led signups.","Use Cal AI to handle inbound scheduling emails without manual back-and-forth."}', 'Sweet spot: a sales, recruiting, or customer-success team where scheduling friction directly costs revenue. At team scale, Calendly''s round-robin, routing forms, and CRM sync collapse a real operational problem (who takes the next call, against what context, with what follow-up) into a configured workflow. The brand recognition is itself a feature — recipients know what to expect from a Calendly link, which removes friction.

Failure modes. Solo users on the free tier feel the 1-event-type cap quickly and either upgrade or churn to a competitor with a more generous free tier (Cal.com, Zcal, TidyCal). Teams that buy Calendly for round-robin without investing in routing-form setup get scheduling, but not the lead-qualification value Calendly is now priced for. Cal AI is genuinely useful but needs prompt-engineering-style setup on which calendars / event types it can use — out of the box it''s conservative.

What to pilot. If you''re a solo professional, the free tier is enough to test the core flow — share the link, book a meeting, confirm the experience. If you''re a team, pilot the Teams tier with one squad: set up round-robin, build one routing form for inbound, connect HubSpot, and measure scheduling-cycle-time reduction over 60 days. If cycle time drops materially, the per-seat cost is justified; if it doesn''t, the bottleneck is upstream of scheduling.', now()),
('Cal.com', 'cal-com', 'Open-source scheduling infrastructure — the Calendly alternative with Cal.ai phone-scheduling assistant.', 'Cal.com is the open-source scheduling platform built by Peer Richelsen and Bailey Pumfleet, backed by Y Combinator (W21) and a growing list of strategic investors. The product is feature-parity with Calendly on the core scheduling primitives — calendar-aware links, round-robin, team scheduling, workflows, embeds — but adds two genuine differentiators: it is open source under the AGPL (self-host the entire platform on your own infrastructure if you want), and it has invested heavily in Cal.ai, an AI scheduling assistant including phone-based booking.

The hosted product (cal.com) gives you everything Calendly has, often with a more generous free tier and a more developer-friendly approach to API access and webhooks. The self-hosted option is what makes Cal.com strategically different — privacy-conscious organisations, regulated industries (healthcare, legal, government), and developer teams who want scheduling embedded deeply in their stack can run the entire platform themselves and own the data.

Cal.ai is the AI layer — a scheduling assistant that handles inbound emails (like Calendly''s Cal) but also includes a phone-based assistant that can answer scheduling calls and book meetings via voice. For service businesses (clinics, salons, professional services) this is genuinely category-defining and not something Calendly currently matches. The product is moving fast; expect rapid feature iteration and occasional rough edges typical of an aggressive open-source startup.', 'https://cal.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Unlimited bookings","Unlimited event types","Calendar integration","Workflows"]},{"plan":"Teams","price":"$15/seat/mo","features":["Round-robin","Routing forms","Team pages","Admin dashboard"]},{"plan":"Organizations","price":"$37/seat/mo","features":["Multi-team management","SSO","Domain management","Advanced reporting"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["Self-hosted option","Dedicated infrastructure","Premium support","SLA"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","mobile","api","desktop"}', '{"Calendar-aware scheduling links","Round-robin team scheduling","Routing forms for lead qualification","Cal.ai email scheduling assistant","Cal.ai phone scheduling assistant (voice booking)","Workflow automations","Embedded scheduling widget","Apps marketplace (100+ integrations)","Open-source codebase (AGPL self-hostable)","Webhooks and full REST API","Multi-language support"}', '{"Google Calendar","Outlook","Office 365","Zoom","Google Meet","Microsoft Teams","Stripe","Salesforce","HubSpot","Zapier","Slack","Notion"}', true, '{"Developer teams embedding scheduling deeply via API","Privacy-conscious organisations needing self-hosting","Service businesses wanting AI phone-based booking","Open-source-first teams avoiding proprietary SaaS lock-in"}', '{"Non-technical solo users who want zero-config setup (Calendly is smoother)","Teams allergic to occasional rough edges in fast-moving products","Buyers who only trust enterprise-grade incumbents"}', 'The credible open-source Calendly alternative — pick it for self-hosting, API depth, or Cal.ai phone scheduling; stay with Calendly for polish and brand recognition.', '{"https://cal.com/docs"}', 'The open-source codebase is excellent but the hosted product still occasionally ships rough edges that a 5-year-old incumbent like Calendly has long since polished — expect occasional UI inconsistencies or feature flag confusion. Self-hosting is real but operationally non-trivial; you need Docker / Kubernetes literacy and ongoing maintenance commitment. Cal.ai phone assistant is impressive but pricing is usage-based and can scale faster than expected on high-volume lines. Brand recognition lags Calendly — recipients sometimes hesitate at unfamiliar booking links.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Self-host scheduling infrastructure for a healthcare org with HIPAA constraints.","Embed a fully white-labelled scheduler into a SaaS product via API.","Deploy Cal.ai phone assistant to handle inbound booking calls for a clinic.","Run round-robin scheduling across a developer-relations team without paying Calendly Enterprise."}', 'Sweet spot: a developer-led team or privacy-conscious organisation that wants Calendly''s functionality but cannot or will not accept Calendly''s closed-source SaaS posture. Cal.com''s open-source AGPL licensing, deeper API surface, and self-host option matter to enough buyers (regulated industries, infra-aware engineering teams, EU privacy-first orgs) to support a real business. Cal.ai''s phone-based booking is also a genuine differentiator for service businesses — voice scheduling that actually works.

Failure modes. The aggressive shipping pace means you''ll occasionally hit a bug or a feature regression that Calendly users would never see. Self-hosting sounds great in slide decks but operationally requires real ongoing engineering investment — most teams that say they want self-hosted Cal.com end up on the hosted product after the first oncall page. Cal.ai is impressive in demos but production usage requires careful prompt and routing setup; treat it as a tool, not magic.

What to pilot. If you''re a developer team, build one integration against the Cal.com API (e.g., embed scheduling into your own product, or push booking events to your data warehouse). If the API ergonomics feel cleaner than Calendly''s — they typically do — Cal.com earns a closer look. If you''re evaluating Cal.ai, run it on a single team''s scheduling load for 30 days and measure rebooking rate, conflict rate, and customer-satisfaction proxy. Above incumbent baselines, scale; below, stick with the existing flow.', now()),
('Typeform', 'typeform', 'Conversational forms and surveys with Formless AI conversational survey layer — the design-first form platform.', 'Typeform is the design-first form platform that pioneered the "one question at a time, conversational" approach to online forms in 2014 and has remained the category brand a decade later. Where Google Forms and SurveyMonkey treat forms as utility, Typeform treats them as brand experiences — clean typography, smooth transitions between questions, conditional logic that branches naturally, and a polish that meaningfully lifts completion rates compared to boxy alternatives.

The 2024–2026 evolution centred on Formless, Typeform''s AI conversational survey product. Instead of authors mapping out every branch and conditional, Formless lets you describe the goal of the survey ("understand why customers churned") and the AI conducts a back-and-forth interview with each respondent, asking follow-ups, probing for depth, and handling open-ended responses naturally. It is one of the more credible "AI-native survey" products in market — not just a wrapper on top of GPT.

Beyond Formless, Typeform covers lead-gen forms, customer feedback surveys, NPS, registration forms, payment-collecting forms (Stripe integration), quizzes, and embedded forms for SaaS sites. Integrations are extensive — Salesforce, HubSpot, Mailchimp, Zapier, Slack, and the rest of the marketing stack. Pricing has moved upmarket as Typeform repositioned from solopreneur tool to revenue-team platform.', 'https://www.typeform.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["10 questions per form","10 responses/mo","Typeform branding","Limited integrations"]},{"plan":"Basic","price":"$25/mo","features":["100 responses/mo","Unlimited questions","Custom subdomain","Remove branding"]},{"plan":"Plus","price":"$50/mo","features":["1,000 responses/mo","Custom domain","Hidden fields","Logic jumps"]},{"plan":"Business","price":"$83/mo","features":["10,000 responses/mo","Conversion tracking","Priority support","Drop-off rates"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Conversational one-question-at-a-time forms","Conditional logic and branching jumps","Formless AI conversational surveys","Quiz and scoring mode","Stripe payment integration","Embeddable forms for any website","Hidden fields for personalisation","File upload questions","Custom thank-you screens with redirect","Conversion analytics and drop-off tracking","Multi-language form support"}', '{"Salesforce","HubSpot","Mailchimp","Zapier","Slack","Google Sheets","Stripe","Airtable","Notion","Calendly"}', true, '{"Marketing teams running lead-gen with high-completion forms","Product teams collecting structured customer feedback","Researchers running qualitative surveys via Formless AI","Event organisers handling registrations with payments"}', '{"Internal-IT teams just needing a basic Google Forms replacement","Budget-constrained solos (cheaper alternatives like Tally exist)","High-volume survey panels needing 100K+ responses (priced for it but pricey)"}', 'The design-first form platform with a credible AI survey product (Formless) layered on top — pick it where completion rates matter, skip it where you just need data capture.', '{"https://www.typeform.com/help/"}', 'Pricing per response can scale fast — high-volume forms quickly push you into Business tier ($83/mo) or beyond. Free tier is heavily capped (10 questions, 10 responses/month) — too limited for most real evaluation. Formless AI is good but conducting a conversation per respondent is more expensive (in credits and time) than a static form, and it''s not the right tool for every survey. The conversational format that lifts B2C completion rates can feel slow and over-designed for internal-team surveys where speed matters more than polish.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Run a high-completion lead-gen form on a marketing landing page with HubSpot sync.","Conduct an AI-driven churn-interview survey using Formless to probe departing customers.","Build a payment-collecting registration form for a workshop with Stripe checkout.","Capture qualitative product feedback with logic-branched follow-up questions."}', 'Sweet spot: a marketing or product team where form completion rate is a measurable revenue lever — typically B2C lead gen, customer feedback surveys, or qualitative research. The conversational format genuinely lifts completion rates compared to traditional forms, which justifies the premium over Google Forms / Tally for revenue-relevant use cases. Formless adds a real new capability (AI-conducted interviews at scale) that no incumbent matches as cleanly.

Failure modes. The most common mistake is buying Typeform for use cases where completion-rate lift doesn''t matter — internal team surveys, simple data capture, low-volume forms — where Tally or Google Forms do the same job for free. The pricing model (per-response tiers) punishes growth: a successful form can suddenly push you into the next tier with no warning. Formless usage discipline matters; an AI interview per respondent at scale is expensive and slow vs. a static form, and it''s not the right answer for every survey.

What to pilot. Take an existing high-traffic lead-gen form (Google Forms, HubSpot embedded form, whatever) and rebuild the same questions in Typeform. A/B test the two against the same traffic for 2 weeks and measure completion rate. If Typeform lifts completion meaningfully (>10–15% relative), the subscription pays for itself in better lead volume. If completion is similar, your form isn''t the bottleneck and Typeform''s premium isn''t justified for that use case.', now()),
('Tally', 'tally-so', 'Notion-like form builder with a generous free plan and no question limits.', 'Tally is a form-building tool that took the Typeform interaction model — one question at a time, conversational pacing, smooth transitions — and rebuilt it on a Notion-like editor where you simply type "/" to insert form blocks. The result is the fastest form-creation experience in the category: most users build their first useful form within five minutes, with no tutorial required.

The product covers what most teams need without forcing an upgrade: unlimited forms, unlimited questions, unlimited submissions on the free tier, conditional logic, calculations, file uploads, payments via Stripe, embeds, custom domains on paid tiers, and integrations with Notion, Airtable, Slack, Google Sheets, HubSpot, and Zapier / Make. The Pro tier unlocks branding removal, custom CSS, hidden fields, and team workspaces.

Tally has become the default form tool for product managers, indie hackers, and startup ops teams through 2024–2026, replacing Typeform for use cases where the $25–$83/month minimum stopped making sense. The free tier is the marketing engine — once a team standardises on Tally, the upgrade to a paid seat tends to follow naturally as the use cases expand.', 'https://tally.so', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["Unlimited forms","Unlimited questions","Unlimited submissions","Basic logic","Tally branding"]},{"plan":"Pro","price":"$29/mo per workspace","features":["Remove Tally branding","Custom domain","File uploads to your storage","Hidden fields","Team workspaces"]},{"plan":"Business","price":"$89/mo per workspace","features":["Custom CSS","Priority support","Advanced integrations","White-label embed"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', false, '{"web"}', '{"Notion-like block editor for fast form building","Unlimited forms, questions, and submissions on free tier","Conditional logic and calculations","Stripe payment collection","File uploads","Embeds (iframe, popup, full-page)","Custom domains (paid)","Hidden fields and URL parameters","Multi-page forms with progress bar","Answer piping and personalisation","Notification emails and Slack alerts"}', '{"Notion","Airtable","Google Sheets","Slack","HubSpot","Stripe","Zapier","Make","Webhooks"}', true, '{"Indie hackers and solopreneurs needing forms without monthly cost","Product managers running quick user research surveys","Startup ops teams collecting structured input from customers","Notion-native teams wanting forms that feed into Notion databases"}', '{"Enterprise teams needing SOC 2 / HIPAA-grade compliance","Survey researchers needing advanced statistical analysis","Teams needing complex multi-step workflows beyond form submission"}', 'The default form tool for indie and startup teams in 2026 — the free tier alone beats most paid competitors.', '{"https://tally.so/help"}', 'No native mobile app — fully web-based, which is fine for builders but means respondents always fill via browser. Analytics are basic compared to Typeform / SurveyMonkey — exports to Sheets / Notion handle most analysis needs but no built-in cross-tabs or statistical tools. Custom branding is locked behind Pro tier. No native A/B testing on form variants. Free tier requires Tally branding on the form footer.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Build a customer feedback form for a SaaS product in 5 minutes with logic branching.","Run a user research survey with 200 responses on the free tier without limits.","Collect job applications with file uploads, syncing answers to a Notion database.","Take Stripe payments for a small workshop or product launch via a Tally form."}', 'Sweet spot: a small team or solo builder who needs forms regularly but doesn''t want to pay $25+/month for Typeform when their volume doesn''t justify it. Tally''s genuine differentiator is the free tier — unlimited forms, unlimited submissions, real logic — which removes the budget conversation entirely for most use cases. The Notion-like editor makes form creation feel like writing a doc, which dramatically lowers the build-time barrier.

Failure modes. If your forms need enterprise-grade compliance (HIPAA, SOC 2 attestations, audit logs), Tally''s Pro tier doesn''t reach that bar — pick Jotform Enterprise or Typeform Enterprise instead. If you need deep analytics or experiment tracking on form variants, Tally''s reporting will frustrate you. And if your respondents are non-technical and on slow connections, Tally''s web-only experience can feel slower than a native-app survey.

What to pilot. Replicate one of your existing Typeform / Google Form workflows in Tally — same questions, same logic, same destination integration. Run both in parallel for two weeks. If completion rates are within 5% and your team prefers the build experience, switching saves real money. If respondents drop off more on Tally, your audience needs a more polished experience and Tally isn''t the right fit yet.', now()),
('PostHog', 'posthog', 'Open-source product analytics, session replay, feature flags, experiments, and LLM observability in one platform.', 'PostHog is an open-source product analytics platform that has steadily absorbed adjacent categories — session replay (Hotjar / FullStory territory), feature flags and experimentation (LaunchDarkly / Optimizely), surveys, error tracking, data warehouse, and most recently LLM observability — into a single integrated suite. The thesis is consolidation: a startup that would have stitched together five SaaS tools can run all of them on PostHog at one bill, with the option to self-host on their own infrastructure if data sovereignty matters.

The product is YC-backed, has grown to a sizeable open-source community, and is widely adopted across early-stage and mid-market product teams. The cloud tier offers a generous free allotment (1M events/month, 5K session recordings, 1M feature flag requests) before billing kicks in on a usage basis — meaning small startups can run PostHog for free indefinitely, and scaling teams pay per event consumed.

PostHog''s architectural bet is to be the data layer for product teams: ingest events once, then use them for analytics dashboards, behavioural cohorts, A/B tests, replay correlation, and LLM trace analysis without re-instrumenting. For teams that already own ClickHouse expertise or want to self-host, PostHog is the rare AI-era tool that gives you full-stack control rather than locking your data into a vendor SaaS.', 'https://posthog.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free Cloud","price":"$0","features":["1M events/mo","5K session recordings/mo","1M feature flag requests/mo","Community support"]},{"plan":"Paid Cloud (usage)","price":"From $0 + usage","features":["Pay-as-you-go beyond free tier","All product features","Email support"]},{"plan":"Teams","price":"$450/mo + usage","features":["SSO/SAML","Role-based access","Audit logs","Priority support"]},{"plan":"Self-Hosted","price":"Free (open source)","features":["Run on your own infra","Full data control","No vendor lock-in"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","api","desktop"}', '{"Product analytics (events, funnels, retention, paths)","Session replay with console and network logs","Feature flags with targeting rules","A/B testing and multivariate experiments","Surveys (in-app and link)","Heatmaps and click maps","Error tracking","Data warehouse with SQL access","LLM observability (prompt traces, costs, evals)","Open-source self-hosting option","SDKs for web, mobile, and server"}', '{"Slack","Segment","Stripe","Salesforce","HubSpot","Webhooks","Zapier","Vercel","Snowflake","BigQuery"}', true, '{"Startups consolidating analytics + replay + flags into one tool","Open-source-first teams wanting self-hosting option","Product teams running experiments without a separate LaunchDarkly bill","AI product teams needing LLM observability alongside product analytics"}', '{"Marketing-led teams primarily tracking ad attribution","Enterprise compliance teams needing certified BI tools (Looker, Tableau)","Non-technical teams without engineering capacity to instrument events"}', 'The most consolidated open-source product analytics suite in 2026 — pick it to replace 3-5 SaaS bills with one platform you can self-host if needed.', '{"https://posthog.com/docs"}', 'Setup requires real engineering investment — proper event taxonomy and SDK integration takes a sprint, not an afternoon. The product surface is wide, which means deeper specialised tools (Amplitude for analytics, FullStory for replay, LaunchDarkly for flags) sometimes have polish PostHog hasn''t matched yet. Self-hosting at scale needs ClickHouse expertise. Cloud usage pricing can grow unpredictably for high-volume products — set billing alerts.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Replace Mixpanel + Hotjar + LaunchDarkly with one consolidated PostHog account.","Self-host PostHog on a startup''s own infrastructure for data sovereignty.","Run a multivariate A/B test on a pricing page with feature flags and conversion analytics tied together.","Trace LLM prompts, costs, and user feedback alongside the product events that triggered them."}', 'Sweet spot: a Series-A or earlier startup with engineering capacity and a strong opinion that owning the analytics layer matters. PostHog''s consolidated stack (analytics + replay + flags + experiments + LLM observability) genuinely replaces 3-5 separate SaaS subscriptions, and the option to self-host removes vendor risk. Teams that adopt PostHog early tend to build instrumentation discipline that pays off as they scale.

Failure modes. PostHog is not a no-code tool — implementing it well requires engineering taste in event design and the willingness to maintain SDK integrations. The breadth of features means each individual surface (heatmaps, surveys, error tracking) is good but not always best-in-class compared to a specialised tool. Cloud usage pricing rewards careful event volume management; teams that fire events on every keystroke get surprised by bills.

What to pilot. Pick one product area — say, your signup funnel — and instrument it fully in PostHog cloud. Run it alongside whatever analytics you currently use for 30 days. Compare insights, replay quality, and the friction of new feature-flag experiments. If PostHog meaningfully reduces tool-switching during a typical product debugging session, the consolidation thesis holds and you can plan the broader migration. If specialised tools still pull you back, run PostHog as a complement instead.', now()),
('Plausible Analytics', 'plausible', 'Privacy-friendly, open-source Google Analytics alternative — lightweight, cookieless, GDPR-friendly.', 'Plausible Analytics is a lightweight, open-source web analytics tool built explicitly as an alternative to Google Analytics. The script weighs under 1KB (versus GA''s ~45KB), uses no cookies, requires no consent banner under GDPR / CCPA / PECR for most use cases, and the entire dashboard fits on a single screen with the metrics that actually matter — visitors, pageviews, bounce rate, sources, top pages, countries, devices.

The product is built and operated by a small distributed team based out of Estonia, fully bootstrapped (no VC), and the codebase is open-source on GitHub with thousands of stars. Customers can use Plausible''s hosted cloud (the most common path) or self-host the entire stack. Either way, all data is owned by the customer and stored in the EU on the cloud tier.

Plausible''s 2026 niche is the privacy-conscious operator: indie SaaS founders, EU-based businesses worried about GA4 legal complexity, and teams that find GA4''s interface genuinely unusable. The product deliberately doesn''t try to compete on feature breadth — there''s no audience-building, no remarketing, no funnel-builder, no AI insights. The selling point is the opposite: a dashboard you actually look at every morning.', 'https://plausible.io', 'paid', '[{"plan":"Growth","price":"$9/mo (10K pageviews)","features":["Up to 50 sites","All core analytics","Email reports","Goals and custom events"]},{"plan":"Business","price":"$19/mo (10K pageviews)","features":["Funnels","Ecommerce revenue","API access","Priority support"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["High-volume tiers","Dedicated support","Custom SLA"]},{"plan":"Self-Hosted","price":"Free (open source)","features":["Run on your own infrastructure","Full data control"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api","desktop"}', '{"Lightweight script (<1KB)","No cookies — no consent banner needed","GDPR / CCPA / PECR friendly by default","Single-page dashboard for fast scanning","Top pages, sources, countries, devices","UTM and campaign tracking","Goals and custom events","Funnel analysis (Business tier)","Ecommerce revenue tracking (Business tier)","Email and Slack reports","Open-source and self-hostable"}', '{"WordPress","Webflow","Ghost","Slack","Google Search Console","API","Zapier","Cloudflare"}', true, '{"Privacy-conscious indie SaaS founders","EU-based businesses avoiding GA4 legal complexity","Bloggers and content sites wanting a dashboard they actually look at","Open-source-first teams wanting self-hosting"}', '{"Marketing teams running heavy ad-attribution analysis","Product teams needing event-level analytics (use Mixpanel / PostHog)","Enterprise teams needing audience segments for remarketing"}', 'The cleanest privacy-friendly Google Analytics alternative in 2026 — pick it for simplicity and GDPR ease, skip it if you need product-analytics depth.', '{"https://plausible.io/docs"}', 'Feature surface is intentionally narrow — no audience builder, no remarketing tags, no built-in A/B testing. Funnels and ecommerce revenue tracking are gated behind the Business tier. Pricing scales with monthly pageviews, which can get expensive fast for high-traffic content sites. Historical data export to BI tools requires API work. Not a replacement for product analytics tools (Mixpanel, PostHog) — it''s a website analytics tool.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Replace Google Analytics on a SaaS marketing site without adding a cookie banner.","Track top blog posts, traffic sources, and goal completions on a daily standup dashboard.","Self-host Plausible on a personal server for a privacy-first portfolio site.","Monitor a product launch in real time with shareable public dashboards."}', 'Sweet spot: an indie SaaS founder, EU operator, or content publisher who wants website analytics that loads instantly, doesn''t need a consent banner, and shows numbers they actually understand. Plausible''s deliberate simplicity is the feature — most teams don''t use 90% of GA4 anyway, and the cognitive cost of GA4''s interface is real. The open-source self-hosting option is a meaningful safety net.

Failure modes. If your business depends on Google / Meta ad attribution, Plausible doesn''t replace GA4 — you still need GA4 for ad-platform integration and lookalike audiences. Pricing scales with pageviews, so a viral content site can blow past the $9/mo tier into the $50–$100+ range fast. And the narrow feature surface means once your analytics needs grow into funnels, cohorts, and event-level tracking, you''ll outgrow Plausible and need PostHog / Mixpanel.

What to pilot. Install Plausible alongside your existing GA4 for 30 days on a single site. Compare the morning-routine experience: which dashboard do you actually open daily? If Plausible wins on speed-to-insight and you''re not running heavy ad campaigns, switch primary analytics. If GA4 still has features you genuinely use weekly, keep both — the Plausible script is light enough that it doesn''t hurt page performance.', now()),
('Mixpanel', 'mixpanel', 'Product analytics platform with AI-powered Spark insights and Boards for fast event-level reporting.', 'Mixpanel is one of the longest-running product analytics platforms — founded in 2009 — and remains a default choice for product teams that need event-level analytics, behavioural cohorts, funnels, retention reports, and experimentation tied to a real user identity model. The 2025 platform refresh added Spark, an AI assistant that takes natural-language questions ("which features did our power users adopt in the last 90 days?") and produces the corresponding chart, cohort, or funnel with a single click.

The product is organised around Boards — collaborative dashboards where teams pin Spark queries, custom reports, and KPI cards — and the new Insights, Funnels, Retention, and Flows reports remain the workhorse views. Mixpanel maintains a generous free tier (up to 1M monthly events, with full feature access on most reports) which has helped it stay competitive against PostHog and Amplitude despite the consolidation pressure in the category.

Mixpanel sits in a specific spot in 2026: it''s the right pick for product teams that want a polished, mature analytics product without committing to PostHog''s wider stack or Amplitude''s enterprise pricing. The Spark AI layer is genuinely useful for non-technical PMs who never quite learned to write Mixpanel queries — it lowers the time-to-insight from minutes to seconds for common questions.', 'https://mixpanel.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Free","price":"$0","features":["1M events/mo","Unlimited reports","Unlimited collaborators","Spark AI (limited)"]},{"plan":"Growth","price":"From $24/mo","features":["10M+ events","Group analytics","Data pipelines","Spark AI","Boards"]},{"plan":"Enterprise","price":"Custom","features":["SSO/SAML","Custom data residency","Dedicated CSM","Advanced governance"]}]'::jsonb, 'intermediate', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Event-level product analytics","Funnels, retention, flows, and cohorts","Spark AI assistant (natural-language to chart)","Boards for collaborative dashboards","Group analytics (account-level metrics)","Behavioural cohorts and segmentation","Data pipelines (Snowflake, BigQuery, Redshift)","JQL and SQL access","SDKs for web, mobile, server","Experimentation reporting","Custom alerts"}', '{"Segment","Snowflake","BigQuery","Redshift","Salesforce","Slack","Amplitude (migration tools)","mParticle","Webhooks"}', true, '{"Product teams needing event-level analytics with mature tooling","PMs who want AI-assisted querying via Spark","SaaS companies tracking account-level metrics","Mobile-app teams needing solid iOS / Android SDKs"}', '{"Marketing-attribution-focused teams (use GA4 / Heap)","Privacy-first sites needing cookieless analytics (use Plausible)","Teams wanting consolidated session replay + flags (use PostHog / Heap)"}', 'A polished, mature product analytics platform with a credible AI layer in Spark — solid choice for SaaS and mobile teams that want depth without committing to PostHog''s wider stack.', '{"https://docs.mixpanel.com/"}', 'Setup quality determines outcome — a sloppy event taxonomy poisons every downstream report. The free tier is generous on events but lacks data pipelines and group analytics, which most growth-stage teams will eventually need. Spark AI is helpful for common questions but still hallucinates on ambiguous business logic — verify every chart it generates. Pricing past 10M events climbs quickly and is opaque without a sales call.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Build a weekly retention cohort report for a SaaS product across 6 months.","Ask Spark ''what did churned users do differently in the 7 days before cancelling'' and pin the result to a Board.","Track in-app feature adoption funnels for a new mobile app release.","Pipe Mixpanel events to Snowflake for joining with billing and CRM data."}', 'Sweet spot: a product team with real engineering capacity to instrument events properly, working on a SaaS or mobile product where understanding behaviour at the event and cohort level matters. Spark closes the gap for non-technical PMs who used to need a data analyst to write JQL queries. Boards make weekly reporting actually collaborative instead of a one-person task.

Failure modes. The most common failure is poor event design at instrumentation — once you have 500 inconsistent events, no AI assistant can untangle them, and you''ll spend a quarter cleaning taxonomy. Mixpanel''s pricing past the free tier is opaque and grows fast on high-volume products. And if your team has already standardised on PostHog or Amplitude, switching to Mixpanel rarely justifies the migration cost.

What to pilot. Instrument one critical user flow — say, signup-to-activation — fully in Mixpanel. Build the funnel, retention, and cohort views, then ask Spark three real questions your team has been arguing about. If Spark produces credible answers in seconds and the team adopts the Boards into their weekly review, Mixpanel earns its seat. If you''re fighting the event model or the Spark answers feel wrong, your instrumentation needs cleanup before any analytics tool will help.', now()),
('Hotjar', 'hotjar', 'Heatmaps, session recordings, and feedback widgets with AI summaries — Contentsquare-owned and widely deployed.', 'Hotjar is the long-standing default for behavioural analytics on websites — heatmaps showing where visitors click and scroll, session recordings showing exactly what users did, on-page surveys, and feedback widgets. Acquired by Contentsquare in 2021, the product has continued to operate under the Hotjar brand and steadily added AI features through 2024–2026: AI-generated session summaries (so PMs don''t have to watch 50 recordings to find the pattern), AI-powered survey question generation, and AI-driven insight surfacing on heatmap data.

The product is organised around three pillars — Observe (heatmaps + recordings), Ask (surveys + feedback widgets), and Engage (user interviews scheduling) — with a generous free tier that captures up to 35 daily sessions on one site, which is enough for most pre-PMF startups to get real value without paying. Pricing scales by monthly identified sessions, with the Plus / Business / Scale tiers unlocking more captured sessions, advanced filters, and integrations.

Hotjar''s 2026 position is the safe, well-known choice — the product most marketing and product teams have used at some point in their career, with extensive documentation, strong WordPress / Shopify / Webflow integrations, and the Contentsquare backing for enterprise needs. The AI summary feature in particular has become a real productivity unlock for teams drowning in recordings.', 'https://www.hotjar.com', 'freemium', '[{"plan":"Basic","price":"$0","features":["35 daily sessions","Unlimited heatmaps","3 surveys","Forever free"]},{"plan":"Plus","price":"$32/mo","features":["100 daily sessions","Unlimited surveys","Filters","Email support"]},{"plan":"Business","price":"$80/mo","features":["500+ daily sessions","Funnels","Custom events","Integrations","Identify API"]},{"plan":"Scale","price":"$171/mo","features":["High-volume capture","SSO","Account-level access","Premium support"]}]'::jsonb, 'beginner', true, '{"web","api"}', '{"Click and scroll heatmaps","Session recordings with rage-click detection","AI-generated session summaries","On-page surveys and NPS widgets","Feedback widget","Funnels (Business tier)","Custom events (Business tier)","User interview scheduling (Engage)","Identify API for user attribution","Filters and segments","WordPress, Shopify, Webflow integrations"}', '{"WordPress","Shopify","Webflow","Slack","HubSpot","Google Analytics","Segment","Zapier","Microsoft Teams"}', true, '{"Marketing teams optimising landing-page conversion","UX researchers needing real-session evidence","Product managers running quick on-page surveys","Small teams wanting one well-known tool for behavioural insight"}', '{"Privacy-strict sites (recordings have GDPR implications even with masking)","Teams needing event-level product analytics (use Mixpanel / PostHog)","High-volume enterprise sites (Contentsquare proper is the right tier)"}', 'The most widely-deployed heatmap and session-replay tool in 2026 — solid choice for marketing-led optimisation, with AI summaries that make recordings actually scalable.', '{"https://help.hotjar.com/"}', 'Recordings have real GDPR / privacy implications — even with input masking enabled, you need consent management and a clear privacy policy. The free tier''s 35 daily sessions is fine for low-traffic sites but fills up fast on real traffic; the jump to Plus is a meaningful step. AI summaries are good for pattern-finding but occasionally miss subtle UX issues a human watcher would catch. Funnels and identify API are gated behind Business tier. Contentsquare ownership means roadmap priorities increasingly align with their enterprise strategy.', '{}', '{"reddit_threads":[]}'::jsonb, '{"Identify rage-click hotspots on a checkout page and prioritise fixes for the next sprint.","Run an exit-intent NPS survey on a pricing page to surface objections.","Use AI summaries to scan 200 session recordings in 10 minutes for common drop-off patterns.","Capture user-side feedback during a redesign launch with the Hotjar feedback widget."}', 'Sweet spot: a marketing or product team that wants behavioural evidence (where users click, where they get stuck, what they say) without setting up the full PostHog / Mixpanel event-instrumentation discipline. Hotjar is install-the-script-and-go — value lands within the first day. AI summaries close the long-standing scalability problem with session recordings, where the watch-time cost used to make recordings only useful for spot-checks.

Failure modes. The biggest failure mode is treating Hotjar as your primary analytics tool — it''s a behavioural / qualitative complement, not a quantitative system of record. Recordings consume engineering time on consent and masking if you''re privacy-strict (EU healthcare, fintech). And once your team grows past the Plus tier, the Business / Scale pricing starts competing with PostHog''s consolidated stack, which can offer replay alongside analytics for similar money.

What to pilot. Install Hotjar on one underperforming page — a landing page with low conversion or a checkout step with high drop-off. Watch 10 sessions yourself, then have AI summarise the next 50. If you find one actionable UX issue you didn''t already know about, the tool earns the Plus tier. If everything you see was already in your bug tracker, you have a different problem (acquisition quality, pricing, intent) and Hotjar won''t solve it.', now());
